Part One - The World

Chapter 1 - Bemelmans Bar

Section 1 - The Street

East Seventy-Sixth Street is a room. "The awning reads THE CARLYLE in white capitals on hunter green, and beneath it a doorman stands with his hands clasped behind his back in the particular posture of a man who has opened the same door forty thousand times and will open it forty thousand more. The brass revolving door catches the last of the November light. Through the glass you can see marble, and warmth, and the promise of a room where someone is playing the piano."

The awning is scenery in East Seventy-Sixth Street. The description is "Hunter green canvas, gold piping, white serif letters. It has been here since 1930. It will be here after you."

The doorman is a man in East Seventy-Sixth Street. The description is "He is perhaps sixty. His overcoat is black and his gloves are white and his face carries the studied neutrality of someone who has seen every kind of person walk through this door and has learned that the ones who hesitate are not always the ones who should." Understand "door man" as the doorman.

Instead of talking to the doorman:
	increase the doorman-talks of the player by 1;
	if the doorman-talks of the player is 1:
		say "'Good evening, sir,' he says, and pulls the door wide without waiting for you to answer. He has already forgotten you. This is not cruelty. This is professionalism.";
	otherwise if the doorman-talks of the player is 2:
		say "He sees you again. Something in his face adjusts—not recognition exactly, not surprise, but the awareness that you are the same man who went in and came back out, and the coming-out has a different posture than the going-in.

'Everything alright, sir?' he says. The question is professional but not empty. He has learned, over thirty-one years at this door, to read the exits. The entrances are all the same—everyone enters with a plan. The exits are where the truth comes out.";
	otherwise if the doorman-talks of the player is 3:
		say "He looks at you the way a man looks at something he has decided to take seriously. 'You know,' he says, 'I've been at this door thirty-one years.' He pauses, recalibrates, decides whether you are someone who wants to hear this. He decides you are. 'I've seen two kinds of people come through. The ones who are coming for the room—the gold, the music, the murals—they come in looking up. And the ones who are coming for someone inside—they come in looking straight ahead. Like they're aiming.'

He adjusts his gloves. 'You came in looking straight ahead,' he says. And then, quieter: 'Most people who come in looking straight ahead leave looking down. But every once in a while one of them leaves looking up. Those are the ones who found something they weren't looking for.'";
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
	otherwise:
		say "The doorman nods at you. The nod says: I have told you what I know. The rest is the door, and the door is open, and it has always been open."

The November air is scenery in East Seventy-Sixth Street. The description is "Cold and clean, with that particular Upper East Side stillness that is not the absence of noise but the presence of money absorbing noise the way good curtains absorb light. Somewhere a few blocks south a siren is going and going and going, and here it sounds like something that is happening to someone else, which it is." Understand "cold" or "wind" or "night" or "sky" as the November air.

The revolving door is scenery in East Seventy-Sixth Street. The description is "Brass and glass, turning on a central axis with the slow deliberation of something that has been dividing inside from outside since 1930. You came through it—or you will, or you are about to, depending on which side of the evening you are standing on. Going back through it would be simple. The door does not lock. The door does not judge. The door divides the warm from the cold and does not care which side you choose." Understand "door" or "brass door" or "glass door" or "glass" as the revolving door.

Section 2 - The Lobby

The Carlyle Lobby is south of East Seventy-Sixth Street. "Black and white marble in a checkerboard so precise it seems to vibrate faintly underfoot. The ceiling is high and the light is the color of old champagne. Ahead the corridor bends leftward, and from around the bend comes the sound of a piano, and ice against crystal, and the low murmur of people who have nowhere else to be and are glad of it.[paragraph break]To the south, the entrance to the bar. A discreet sign to the west indicates the restrooms."

The marble floor is scenery in the Carlyle Lobby. The description is "You can see your reflection in it, darkly. You look fine. You look like someone who belongs here. This is the first thing you learned: you belong wherever you decide you belong."

Section 3 - The Bar

Bemelmans Bar is south of the Carlyle Lobby. "This is the room.

It is smaller than you imagined. The murals wrap around all four walls—Ludwig Bemelmans painted them himself in 1947, in exchange for a year and a half of lodging for his family. Central Park rendered in the style of a man who also drew a little French girl named Madeline: elephants skating on a frozen pond, rabbits in top hats promenading along the Mall, a horse-drawn carriage passing bare winter trees. The colors are muted, autumnal, as though the park exists in a season that never quite arrives.

The ceiling is gold leaf. Not gold-colored. Twenty-four karat gold leaf, and in the lamplight from the small shaded table lamps it seems to pulse very faintly, as though the room itself were breathing. This is not a bar. This is a clearing—a place where light comes through and things become visible, where the gold makes everything beneath it show up more fully than it would in ordinary light, the way a clearing in a forest is not the trees or the sky but the openness itself, the precondition for anything appearing at all. The bar runs along the south wall, dark wood polished to the point of philosophy. Behind it [if James is known]James[otherwise]the bartender[end if] is pouring something precise.

The piano is in the northwest corner. The pianist is playing something by Cole Porter that you almost recognize—one of the ones about love that sounds like it might be about something else entirely.

[if Catherine is known]Catherine is here, seated at the bar. Margaux is beside her.[otherwise]A dark-haired woman is seated at the bar. Another woman is beside her.[end if]"

The murals are scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Bemelmans painted them over the course of several months. He drank steadily throughout, by all accounts. On the east wall the elephants are skating and a rabbit watches from behind a bare oak. On the west the park is in summer, the leaves impossibly green, a rabbit in a straw boater doffing his hat. The animals are gentle and oblivious. They do not know they are being watched. They have been not-knowing this for sixty years."

The gold ceiling is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Twenty-four karat. Twelve thousand square inches of it, applied leaf by leaf by hand. In the lamplight it moves. Not actually moves. But something."

The bar counter is a supporter in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Dark wood, very old, polished every day for sixty years by hands that understood that the surface of a bar is a kind of contract between the house and the guest. There is a small bowl of mixed nuts. The nuts are warm."

The bowl of nuts is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Warm, salted, in a small white porcelain bowl. The method has no position on bar nuts. This is one of its few silences that is not strategic."

The piano is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "A baby grand, black, its lid propped open like a jaw in mid-sentence. The pianist's hands move over the keys with the easy economy of someone who has played this room a thousand nights and knows that the music is not the point. The music is the weather. It makes the room possible."

The table lamps are scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Small, shaded, casting circles of amber light that each table wears like a halo. Between the circles the room is dark enough to be generous."

The bar stools are scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Upholstered in dark leather, backless, set at the precise height that makes sitting at a bar feel like a minor act of performance—you are slightly elevated, slightly exposed, arranged for display in a way that chairs at tables are not. The method has opinions about where you sit and how you sit and what your posture communicates. The stools do not care about your posture. The stools have supported sixty years of postures and have formed no opinions." Understand "stool" or "stools" or "seat" or "seats" as the bar stools.

The bar windows are scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "The November dark presses against them from outside. Through the glass the city is a smear of headlights and bare branches and the particular amber of streetlamps on the Upper East Side, which is a different amber from the room's amber—colder, less conspiratorial. In here the light is the color of old champagne and the ceiling is gold and everything is arranged for warmth. Out there is November and the rest of your life. The method does not distinguish between the two. The method says the room is a venue and the venue is a variable. The window says otherwise. The window says there are two worlds and you are in one of them and the other one is waiting." Understand "window" or "windows" as the bar windows.

Catherine's drink is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "Something clear with a twist of something pale—lime, probably, a thin crescent resting against the glass like a parenthetical remark. She ordered it before you arrived. She will order another after you leave, or she will not, and neither outcome will have anything to do with you. The drink is hers the way her name is hers, the way her evening is hers—you are a guest in all of it, and the method's deepest confusion is the belief that the guest can become the host." Understand "her drink" or "her glass" or "clear drink" or "vodka" or "twist" as Catherine's drink.

Margaux's martini is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "She holds it with [if Margaux is open]both hands now, the glass cradled rather than wielded, the olive sitting at the bottom like a small green period at the end of a sentence she has decided to finish[otherwise]one hand, the stem between her fingers, the glass positioned at exactly the height of casual conversation, which is to say the height of a barrier that pretends to be a gesture[end if]. The method calls her the obstacle. Her drink is the obstacle's obstacle." Understand "martini" or "olive" as Margaux's martini.

The pianist's water glass is scenery in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "A plain glass of water, no ice, sitting on the piano's closed music stand. He takes a sip between songs—never during, never rushing, a sip that is part of the rhythm the way a rest is part of the music. The water is the most ordinary thing in this room. He drinks it the way he plays—without performance, without self-consciousness, with the calm of a man who has been doing this so long that even his thirst has become a kind of grace." Understand "water" or "water glass" as the pianist's water glass.

Section 4 - The Far End

The Far End of the Bar is east of Bemelmans Bar. "A few small tables here, half-hidden behind a column sheathed in dark wood. The murals continue—on this wall the park is deep in winter, the trees skeletal, the pond frozen, a single rabbit standing at the water's edge looking at its own reflection. The light is softer. This is where conversations go when they want to become something else.

A banquette runs along the wall, upholstered in dark brown leather that has absorbed sixty years of whispered things."

The banquette is an enterable supporter in the Far End of the Bar. The description is "Leather, dark brown, soft from decades of use. The kind of seat that holds you the way a conversation holds you—loosely, but with intent."

The winter mural is scenery in the Far End of the Bar. The description is "The rabbit at the edge of the frozen pond. It is looking down at the ice, at its own reflection, with an expression that Bemelmans somehow rendered as something between curiosity and recognition. The trees behind it are bare. The sky is the gray of a November afternoon that never ends."

The scratched initials are scenery in the Far End of the Bar. The description is "Someone, years ago, scratched a set of initials into the plaster beside the banquette. They have been painted over and the initials have been scratched again, or different initials by a different hand, the plaster scarred with the evidence that someone was here once and wanted the wall to know. The wall knows. The wall does not care. But it holds the information anyway, the way walls do." Understand "initials" or "plaster" or "wall" as the scratched initials.

Section 5 - The Restroom

The Restroom is west of the Carlyle Lobby. "White marble and bright light. After the gold dimness of the bar the fluorescence is almost clinical—the light of a place that does not trade in atmosphere, that has no interest in making you look good or feel welcome, that exists only to serve a function and reflects this commitment in every surface.

A long mirror runs above the sinks. The faucets are brass. There is a small wicker basket of hand towels, each one folded into a precise rectangle, and an attendant's station with a dish for tips. The attendant is not here. It is a Tuesday. On Tuesdays you are alone with the mirror."

The restroom mirror is scenery in the Restroom. The description is "You see yourself. Not the version from the bar—not the man in the lamplight, the man the gold ceiling was kind to, the man who scanned the room and identified the set and felt his confidence tick upward like a dial. This version is harsher. The blazer is just a blazer. The shirt is just a shirt. The eleven-hundred-dollar watch is just a watch that cost eleven hundred dollars and is not worth eleven hundred dollars and everyone in the room, including you, has agreed not to mention this.

Your face. You are looking at your face. It is the face of a man who memorized a manual on a subject that should not have a manual, and the face knows this, and the knowing is visible in the particular set of the jaw, the particular tension around the eyes, the particular expression that Bemelmans would have given to one of his rabbits—alert, slightly lost, trying to determine whether the pond is frozen enough to stand on.

The method was invisible in the bar. The method withdrew into its own functioning—you did not experience 'I am executing a technique,' you experienced the conversation flowing, the warmth increasing, the evening working. The method disappeared the way a tool disappears when it is working properly. But here, in this light, the method is visible. You can see it. You can see the whole apparatus—the forum, the book, the eight months, the sequence—the way you see a window when the glass cracks. The cracking is the restroom. The fluorescent light is the crack. And in the cracking, the world the method was concealing is briefly, painfully, visible: a man in a bar who wants something he does not know how to want without a system."

The brass faucets are scenery in the Restroom. The description is "Brass, old, the kind that require you to hold them open with one hand while you wash with the other—a small act of coordination that forces you to be present, to be here, to not be thinking about the set."

The hand towels are scenery in the Restroom. The description is "White, folded, stacked with the care of someone who believes that even the smallest courtesies matter. You take one. It is warm." Understand "towels" or "towel" or "basket" as the hand towels.

The tip dish is scenery in the Restroom. The description is "A small porcelain dish with a few bills in it—ones, a five—left by men who passed through here on their way between one version of themselves and another. The attendant is not here to collect them. The tips sit in the dish like small prayers left at an altar no one is tending. You consider leaving something. You are not sure what you would be paying for. The mirror, perhaps. The use of the mirror. The brief permission to see yourself without the gold ceiling telling you what to see." Understand "dish" or "tips" or "money" or "bills" as the tip dish.

Section 6 - The Corner

The Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison is east of East Seventy-Sixth Street. "The corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. The traffic light changes from green to yellow to red and back again, performing its sequence for an audience of no one. The method is not the only system that runs whether or not anyone is watching. The city is full of systems—traffic lights, subway schedules, the opening and closing of automatic doors—all of them cycling through their sequences with the same blind faith in the sequence that brought you here tonight.

The Carlyle is to the west, its awning a dark green brushstroke in the amber streetlight. Madison Avenue runs north and south."

The traffic light is scenery in the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. The description is "Green. Yellow. Red. Green. Yellow. Red. The cycle is sixty seconds. The cycle does not care that no one is crossing. The cycle is the city's most honest performance—a system that does exactly what it was built to do, for no audience, with no score. You watch it change three times. You are aware that watching a traffic light change is not a move in any sequence you know. This is either wasted time or the most valuable thing you have done all night. The traffic light does not distinguish." Understand "light" or "traffic" or "signal" as the traffic light.

The street trees are scenery in the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. The description is "Bare. November. The branches make a kind of calligraphy against the sky that you would not notice if you were calculating your next move. You are not calculating your next move. The branches are beautiful the way things are beautiful when you stop assigning them a function." Understand "trees" or "tree" or "branches" as the street trees.

Section 7 - Madison Avenue

North on Madison is north of the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. "Madison Avenue, looking north. The sidewalk stretches ahead in that particular Upper East Side way—wide, clean, canopied by bare trees. Gallery windows, dark. A pharmacy, closed. The mannequins in a boutique window stand in positions of arrested confidence that remind you, uncomfortably, of the posture the method teaches—shoulders back, chest open, chin level, the geometry of a body that is not waiting for permission.

The street is empty in the way that expensive streets are empty at night—not abandoned but curated, the absence itself a kind of display."

The mannequins are scenery in North on Madison. The description is "Three of them, in a window lit from within. They are wearing next season's collection, or this season's, it does not matter—the clothes are arranged on bodies that cannot choose to wear them, that cannot shrug them off, that have been posed by someone else's hands into positions of confidence and ease. The mannequins have perfect posture. The mannequins have outcome-independence. The mannequins have mastered the art of appearing to not need anything, which is the method's highest aspiration, and the mannequins are empty, which is the method's deepest fear, and you are standing on a sidewalk at night looking through glass at the intersection of those two facts." Understand "mannequin" or "boutique" or "window" or "display" as the mannequins.

The closed pharmacy is scenery in North on Madison. The description is "Dark inside, the shelves barely visible, bottles and boxes arranged in rows of manufactured remedy. Everyone who walks in here is looking for a fix—something for the headache, the cold, the insomnia. You wonder if they sell anything for the particular condition you have, the condition of being a man who has systematized desire and is now standing on Madison Avenue at night wondering whether the system is the desire or the thing that replaced the desire, and the pharmacist, if the pharmacist were here, would have no answer, because this is not a condition with a shelf." Understand "pharmacy" or "drugstore" as the closed pharmacy.

South on Madison is south of the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. "Madison Avenue, looking south. The storefronts give way to something less curated—a dry cleaner, a nail salon, both dark—and then, half a block down, the unmistakable fluorescence of a place that is still open. Its light spills onto the sidewalk like a confession: honest, unflattering, utterly without atmosphere.

You can enter the diner to the south."

Section 8 - East on Seventy-Sixth

East Seventy-Sixth toward Park is east of the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison. "East on Seventy-Sixth Street, away from the Carlyle. Brownstones, quiet, the residential hush of old money sleeping behind curtains that cost more than your blazer. A single lit window on the third floor of a limestone building—someone up late, reading or working or lying awake thinking about something that has nothing to do with you, and the not-having-to-do-with-you is the most restful thought you have had all evening.

A bench sits under a bare tree. The bench is iron and cold and public in a way that nothing in the Carlyle is public."

The park bench is an enterable supporter in East Seventy-Sixth toward Park. The description is "Iron, painted green, the paint chipping in places to reveal older paint beneath—green over green over green, layers of municipal care applied and reapplied by hands you will never see for a public you will never thank. The bench asks nothing of you. You can sit on it or not. You can stay or go. The bench has no three-second rule. The bench has no method. The bench is the most liberated object you have encountered tonight." Understand "bench" or "seat" as the park bench.

Instead of entering the park bench:
	say "You sit down. The iron is cold through the fabric of your trousers. The street is quiet. Above you the bare branches hold the sky the way a hand holds water—loosely, temporarily, knowing it will spill.

You are sitting on a bench on the Upper East Side in November and you are not running a sequence. You are not tracking variables. You are not calculating the optimal next move. You are sitting on a bench and the bench is cold and the sky is held by bare branches and the city is making its sounds—a distant siren, a car on Park Avenue, the low hum of a building's ventilation system breathing for the people sleeping inside it—and none of these sounds are data and none of them are signals and none of them are the method and all of them are the evening, the actual evening, the one that was happening this whole time while you were in the gold room trying to make a different evening happen.";
	increase the explored of the player by 1;
	now the player is on the park bench.

The lit window is scenery in East Seventy-Sixth toward Park. The description is "Third floor, limestone building. The light is warm—a reading lamp, probably, or a desk lamp, the kind of light that is meant for one person in one room doing one thing. Someone is up late. You do not know them. They do not know you. The mutual not-knowing is the most honest relationship you have had all evening. Neither of you is performing. Neither of you is tracking. Neither of you is running a system on the other. You are a man on a bench and they are a person behind a window and the distance between you is the width of a sidewalk and three stories of limestone and a life you will never enter, and the distance is not a problem to be solved. The distance is the thing itself." Understand "window" or "light" or "lit window" as the lit window.

Section 9 - The Diner

The Diner is south of South on Madison. "It is a diner in the way that the Carlyle is a hotel—the word is technically correct but it is the wrong container for what is actually here. Formica counters, a coffee machine that has been on since morning, a display case of pastries under a light that makes everything look faintly green. The menu is laminated. The clock on the wall is seventeen minutes slow, or the evening is seventeen minutes fast, depending on whose time you trust.

There is no gold ceiling. There are no murals. There is no pianist. There is a man behind the counter and a coffee machine and the particular silence of a place that has stopped pretending it is anything other than what it is."

The diner counter is a supporter in the Diner. The description is "Formica, cream-colored with a pattern of small boomerangs that was modern in 1961 and is now a kind of archaeology. The surface is clean. It has been wiped by the same man a thousand times. The wiping is not polished-to-the-point-of-philosophy. The wiping is just wiping. The surface is clean because a man wiped it. This is the simplest relationship in the world between a person and a task, and it does not require a method."

The diner coffee machine is scenery in the Diner. The description is "It has been on since six this morning. The coffee inside it has been getting worse by the hour in the particular way that diner coffee gets worse—not spoiling exactly, just concentrating, becoming more itself, more essentially coffee, the way a truth becomes more true the longer you look at it. The machine does not know what a pour-over is. The machine does not know what cold brew is. The machine knows heat and water and ground beans and time, and from these four ingredients it produces something that is not good and is not bad and is exactly what it is." Understand "coffee machine" or "coffee" or "machine" as the diner coffee machine.

The laminated menu is scenery in the Diner. The description is "Eggs. Toast. Coffee. Pie. The menu is a list of things a human body might want at any hour, and the list has not changed since the menu was laminated, and the lamination has yellowed, and the yellowing is a kind of patience—the patience of a list that knows it will never need updating because human hunger does not innovate." Understand "menu" as the laminated menu.

The diner man is a man in the Diner. The printed name of the diner man is "man behind the counter". The description is "He is perhaps sixty, with the particular patience of someone who has been sitting behind this counter so long that the counter has become a part of his body the way the bar counter is a part of James's body—except James's counter is dark wood polished to the point of philosophy and this counter is Formica wiped to the point of clean, and the difference between philosophy and clean is the difference between the Carlyle and this diner, which is the difference between performance and function, which is a difference the method would understand but would misread, because the method would say the Carlyle has higher value, and the method would be wrong in a way that is difficult to articulate and easy to feel." Understand "man" or "counter man" or "diner man" or "guy" as the diner man.

The diner man has a number called diner-talks. The diner-talks of the diner man is 0.

Instead of talking to the diner man:
	increase the diner-talks of the diner man by 1;
	increase the explored of the player by 1;
	if the diner-talks of the diner man is 1:
		say "'Coffee?' he says, without looking up from the crossword. The question is not really a question. It is a diagnosis. You are a man standing in a diner at this hour, and men standing in diners at this hour want coffee.

'Yeah,' you say. 'Coffee.'

He pours it. He sets it in front of you. The cup is white, thick, the kind of cup that does not know what bone china is. The coffee is terrible. The coffee is the most honest liquid you have encountered tonight. It does not catch the lamplight. It does not have the color of dark honey. It is brown and hot and it costs two dollars and it will do exactly what it promises to do, which is warm you from the inside, and the promise is kept before you finish the cup.

'You alright?' he says, and the question is real, and the realness of it lands the way the bourbon did not—not as a prop, not as a signal, but as a thing one person says to another person when the hour is late and the diner is empty and the asking is free.

'Yeah,' you say. 'I'm alright.'

'Good,' he says, and goes back to the crossword. A four-letter word for something. He does not tell you what. You do not ask.";
	otherwise if the diner-talks of the diner man is 2:
		say "'Refill?' he says. You nod. He pours. The pouring is identical to James's pouring—the same economy of motion, the same unhurried precision—and the similarity is the most unsettling thing you have noticed all evening, because it means the grace was never the Carlyle's. The grace was in the pouring. The pouring is the same in a diner and in a bar with a gold ceiling, and the gold ceiling was never what made it beautiful, and you have spent the whole evening in the wrong room, or you have spent the whole evening in the right room and are only now standing in the room that shows you why.

He glances at the crossword. 'Seven across,' he says, to no one in particular. 'Eighteen letters. [italic type]A persistent illusion[roman type].' He taps the pen against the counter. 'Einstein said that. About time. Time is a persistent illusion.' He looks at the pen, then at you. 'You know what's funny about this pen? I've had it eleven years. Eleven years, same pen. When it works I don't even know I'm holding it. It's just—' he makes a writing gesture, '—part of the hand. The crossword happens and the pen's not there. But last week the ink ran out and I spent twenty minutes looking for another one and the whole time I'm thinking about the pen. Eleven years I never thought about it. Ink runs out and suddenly it's the only thing in the room.' He shrugs. 'Everything works like that, I think. Everything hides the thing it's for. Coffee machine hides the fact that people need to stay awake. The crossword hides the fact that I need something to do with my hands on a slow night. You only see what a thing's for when the thing stops working.'

He looks at you. 'You got somewhere to be?'

'I don't know,' you say, and it is the second honest thing you have said tonight, after [italic type]I'm trying to be[roman type], and it costs nothing, and it is worth everything, and the diner holds it the way the gold room held the other one—gently, without comment, without score.";
	otherwise:
		say "The man behind the counter nods at you. The nod is James's nod and the doorman's nod and the pianist's nod—the universal nod of men who are at their posts, who know their stations, who have been doing what they do long enough that the doing has become a form of presence rather than a form of labor. The nod says: I am here. You are here. The coffee is here. That is enough."

Chapter 2 - Ambient Life

The pianist is a man in Bemelmans Bar. The description is "He is perhaps fifty, thin, in a dark suit. He plays without looking at his hands. Between songs he takes a sip from a glass of water on the piano and then begins the next piece as though it were the same piece, as though all the songs were one song and the pauses between them were just the song breathing." Understand "piano man" or "piano player" as the pianist.

The pianist can be playing or resting. The pianist is playing.

The pianist's break is a scene. The pianist's break begins when the turn count is greater than 15 and the player is in Bemelmans Bar and the pianist is playing. The pianist's break ends when the time since the pianist's break began is 6 minutes.

When the pianist's break begins:
	now the pianist is resting;
	say "The pianist lifts his hands from the keys. The last note hangs in the air for a moment and then the room absorbs it, the way the room absorbs everything—sound, light, time, the small evidence that people were here. He reaches for his water, takes a slow sip, and stands. He stretches his back with the careful deliberation of a man who knows exactly which vertebrae are going to object, and then he sits back down on the bench, turned away from the keys now, facing the room."

When the pianist's break ends:
	now the pianist is playing;
	say "The pianist turns back to the keys. He plays the first few notes of something you do not recognize—not Cole Porter this time, something older, something that sounds like it was written by someone who had been in a room like this and understood that the music's job is not to be heard but to make the hearing of everything else possible. The room settles back into its rhythm. The weather resumes."

Instead of talking to the pianist:
	if the pianist is playing:
		say "He nods at you without interrupting the melody, the way a river acknowledges a stone.";
	otherwise:
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
		say "He is sitting on the bench, turned toward the room, his back to the keys. Up close he is older than you thought—the lines around his eyes are deep and specific, the lines of a man who has spent decades squinting at charts in low light.

'You're the one who's been standing by the bar,' he says. Not accusingly. The way you would note the weather. 'I can always tell when someone is listening to the music and when someone is listening to the room. You were listening to the room. The music is just the thing that makes the room hearable.'

He takes a sip of water. 'I've been playing Porter in here for nine years. Before that, standards. Before that, I played jazz in a basement on Bleecker and nobody came and it was the best playing of my life, because when nobody listens you play for the room, and when you play for the room the room plays back.' He turns the water glass in his hands. 'Here, people listen. It's different. It's not worse. But the room is quieter when it's being listened to. Even the room performs.'

He sets down the glass. 'Do you play?' he asks, and the question is not about music."

James is a man in Bemelmans Bar. The printed name of James is "[if James is known]James[otherwise]bartender[end if]". Understand "bartender" or "barman" or "barkeeper" as James. Understand "James" as James when James is known. The description is "[if James is known]James. You know his name now, which means you have crossed from customer to something adjacent to regular, which is its own small form of intimacy that the method does not catalog. White[otherwise]The bartender. White[end if] jacket, black bow tie, hands that move with the unhurried precision of a watchmaker. He has been here eleven years. He remembers what everyone drinks. He will remember what you drink. He does not remember names. This is policy, not incapacity."

Instead of talking to James:
	increase the james-talks of the player by 1;
	if the james-talks of the player is 1:
		say "'What can I get you?' he says, and his eyes meet yours for exactly the right duration—long enough to mean [italic type]I see you[roman type], short enough to mean [italic type]and I will not make a thing of it[roman type].";
	otherwise if the james-talks of the player is 2:
		say "[if James is known]James[otherwise]The bartender[end if] looks at you with the particular attention of a man whose profession is attention. 'First time here?' he asks, and before you answer: 'I can always tell. It's the ceiling. First-timers look up at least three times in the first five minutes.' He says this without judgment, the way a doctor reports a heartbeat—observable, unremarkable, one more reading in a career of readings. 'You looked up four,' he adds, and goes back to polishing.";
	otherwise if the james-talks of the player is 3:
		say "'Bemelmans was drunk when he painted most of this,' [if James is known]James[otherwise]the bartender[end if] says, nodding at the murals. 'Not falling-down drunk. Painting drunk. Steady-hand drunk. The kind of drunk that loosens something in the wrist without touching the eye.' He polishes a glass that is already clean. 'People think the rabbits are whimsical. They're not. Look at the one by the pond.' He nods toward the far end. 'Bemelmans gave that rabbit the most human expression in the room. The people in his other paintings—the little girl, the nuns—they're cartoons. The rabbit is real. He put everything real into the animals and everything performed into the people.' A beat. 'I think about that sometimes.'";
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
	otherwise if the james-talks of the player is 4:
		say "[if James is known]James[otherwise]The bartender[end if] sets down his cloth. He is quiet for a moment—not the professional quiet, not the courtesy quiet, but the quiet of a man deciding whether to open a door.

'There was a couple,' he says. 'Used to come every Tuesday. Thirty years. Not twenty-nine, not thirty-one. Thirty. I started here in my twenties and they were already old, already ordering the same thing—Gibson for him, Sancerre for her, the small bowl of nuts between them. They never changed. The room changed. The music changed. Three different pianists. The menu rewrote itself four times. They never changed.'

He picks up the cloth, puts it down again.

'Then one Tuesday it was just him. He sat in the same seat. I poured the Gibson. And then I poured the Sancerre. I put it on the bar next to the empty stool. He didn't say anything. I didn't say anything. The Sancerre sat there all night. He drank his Gibson. He paid for both. He left.'

'He came back the next Tuesday. And the next. Every Tuesday for a year. I poured both drinks every time. Neither of us ever mentioned it.'

He is looking at the bar surface now, at the dark wood, at the sixty years of polish.

'And then one Tuesday he didn't come. And I knew. And I poured both drinks anyway, and both of them sat on the bar all night, and the gold ceiling held the light, and the pianist played the same songs, and the room was the room. And I closed out the tab and poured both drinks down the sink. And that was the last Tuesday.'

He picks up the cloth. 'People think a bartender is furniture,' he says. 'Something to stand behind a counter and pour. But the counter is the best seat in the house. You see everyone. You see the whole room. You see the ones who are trying and the ones who have stopped trying and the ones who never needed to try. And you pour, and you polish, and you remember. Because someone has to remember. The gold ceiling won't do it. The rabbits won't do it. Someone has to hold the room's memory, and it might as well be the man with the cloth.'";
		increase the explored of the player by 2;
	otherwise:
		say "[if James is known]James[otherwise]The bartender[end if] nods at you—the nod of a man who has said what he had to say and is now content to pour, to polish, to be the fixed point around which the evening turns."

Part Two - The People

Chapter 1 - Social Architecture

