Chapter 4 - The Woman With the Notebook

The notebook woman is a woman in Bemelmans Bar. The printed name of the notebook woman is "woman with the notebook". Understand "woman with notebook" or "notebook woman" or "notebook" or "writer" as the notebook woman.

The description of the notebook woman is "She is sitting at a corner table, alone, writing something in a notebook with a pen that moves in small, precise strokes. She is perhaps forty-five, with gray at her temples and reading glasses pushed up on her forehead and the particular posture of a woman who is comfortable being alone in public—who has been alone in public enough times that it has become a form of companionship, not with anyone else but with herself, with the notebook, with whatever is being written. A glass of red wine sits beside her, half-drunk, forgotten in the way that drinks are forgotten by people who came here for something other than drinking."

The notebook woman has a number called notebook-talks. The notebook-talks of the notebook woman is 0.

The notebook woman has a text called private-thought. The private-thought of the notebook woman is "She is a novelist. She has published two books that were well-reviewed and poorly sold and she is working on a third that she is not sure about, that she comes here to work on because her apartment is too quiet and coffee shops are too loud and Bemelmans Bar on a Tuesday is exactly right—warm enough, dim enough, beautiful enough to remind her that beauty is still possible, which is the thing she needs to believe in order to write. She does not know she is in a game. She does not know that the man at the bar is running a system on the woman three stools down. She is watching, from the corner of her eye, the way a novelist watches: without agenda, without judgment, with the particular patience of a person whose profession is the patient observation of other people's lives."

Rule for writing a paragraph about the notebook woman:
	say "At a corner table, a woman is writing in a notebook, a glass of red wine beside her, her reading glasses catching the lamplight."

Instead of talking to the notebook woman:
	increase the notebook-talks of the notebook woman by 1;
	increase the explored of the player by 1;
	if the notebook-talks of the notebook woman is 1:
		say "She looks up. The reading glasses catch the lamplight. 'Sorry,' she says, 'I was—' She gestures at the notebook with the pen, a wave that encompasses everything she was doing and dismisses it simultaneously. Then she looks at you properly, with the appraising directness of someone who has spent years looking at things properly.

'You've been standing at the bar for a while,' she says. 'Are you waiting for someone or watching someone?'

The question is not judgmental. It is precise. She is a person who asks precise questions because imprecise ones waste time, and time in this room costs twenty-two dollars a drink, and she is a woman for whom twenty-two dollars is not nothing.";
	otherwise if the notebook-talks of the notebook woman is 2:
		say "'I come here to write,' she says, as though you had asked, which you didn't, but she has decided that the silence between your visits to her table constitutes a question. 'My apartment is too quiet. I know that sounds like a contradiction—a writer wanting noise. But it's not noise I want. It's presence. Other people existing in the room. The sound of ice and conversation and—' she nods toward the piano, '—music that isn't trying to be listened to. That's the perfect background. Music that is trying to be weather.'

She takes a sip of wine. 'I've been watching you, by the way. Not in a creepy way. In a novelist way, which might be worse.' A slight smile. 'You're very busy. You've been very busy since you walked in. You keep—' she moves her hand in a pattern, a choreography, '—doing things. To people. In a sequence. It's fascinating. It looks exhausting.'";
	otherwise if the notebook-talks of the notebook woman is 3:
		say "She has closed the notebook. This feels significant—a writer closing her notebook to talk to you means you have become more interesting than the sentence she was trying to get right.

'Can I tell you something?' she says. 'A thing I've noticed? Not about you specifically—about people in this room, over the years. The ones who are working the hardest are the ones who are least present. They're here but they're not [italic type]here[roman type]. They're in the next move. They're in the sequence. And the room—this room especially—the room can tell. The gold ceiling can tell.' She taps the notebook with her pen. 'I once wrote a whole chapter about a man in a bar who was trying so hard to be interesting that he became invisible. The effort was the thing that erased him. The trying was the disappearing.'

She opens the notebook again, finds the page. 'Here,' she says. 'I wrote this tonight.' She turns the notebook toward you, briefly—you catch a fragment, a sentence, handwritten in small precise script: [italic type]He carries himself like a man who has memorized the instructions for being a person and is executing them in order, and the execution is flawless, and the flawlessness is the tell.[roman type]

She turns the notebook back. 'Sorry,' she says. 'Occupational hazard. I see things and I write them down. You can be angry if you want.'";
		increase the explored of the player by 2;
	otherwise:
		say "The woman with the notebook gives you a small wave from her corner table. The wave says: I am here. I see you. I have said what I was going to say. The notebook is open again. The pen is moving. You have been written, or you are being written, or the act of writing you and the act of being you are happening at the same time, in the same room, under the same gold ceiling, and neither of them knows which one is more real."

Chapter 5 - The Player

The player is a man called Ethan. The description is "[if the player is in the Restroom]You are standing in front of the mirror in the restroom of the Carlyle Hotel. In this light you are not the man from the bar. You are the man from before the bar—the man from the apartment, from the forum, from the eight months of study. The blazer is the same blazer. The watch is the same watch. But the gold ceiling is not here to gild you, and without it you are just a man who got dressed for something and is not yet sure whether the something is happening.[otherwise]You are wearing a dark blazer over a white shirt, no tie. Your shoes are clean. Your posture is the posture the method teaches—shoulders back, chest open, chin level, the geometry of a man who is not waiting for permission. Your watch is an Omega Seamaster, purchased on eBay for eleven hundred dollars—close enough to real to pass, far enough from real to remind you that everything tonight is a performance, including the parts that are not.[end if]"

The player has a number called confidence. The confidence of the player is 5.
The player has a number called outcome-independence. The outcome-independence of the player is 3.

The player has a text called wing-status. The wing-status of the player is "Marcus texted forty minutes ago: [italic type]sorry bro, work thing, next time[roman type]. There will not be a next time, or there will, and it will be the same text. You are alone. This is fine. The method works alone. The method is designed to work alone, because ultimately you are always alone, and the method knows this about you even if you do not."

The player has a text called backstory. The backstory of the player is "Eight months ago you were a different person, or the same person without a system. You were the man at the end of the bar nursing a drink and watching other men talk to women and wondering what they knew that you did not. Then you found the forum. Then you read the book. Then you read the other book, and the other one, and the field reports, hundreds of them, men writing about their nights in a language stripped of everything that makes nights worth having. And something in the language worked on you the way a solvent works on paint—it dissolved the surface, and beneath the surface were the mechanics, and the mechanics could be learned, and you learned them, and here you are."

The phone is a thing carried by the player. The printed name of the phone is "phone". Understand "phone" or "cell" or "cell phone" or "mobile" or "screen" as the phone.

The description of the phone is "[if the interest of Catherine is 0 and the player is in Bemelmans Bar]The screen glows. Marcus's text is still there: [italic type]sorry bro, work thing, next time[roman type]. Below it, the forum. You were reading a field report on the subway—some guy in Chicago, a three-set at a hotel bar, clean isolation, number close. He wrote it in the method's language and the method's language made it sound like a successful mission briefing, and it was, and it was also a man alone at two in the morning writing about a woman whose name he had already converted to a code—HB7, HB8—because the code was easier to carry than the name.[otherwise if the interest of Catherine is greater than 0 and the player is in Bemelmans Bar]The phone is in your pocket. You are aware of it the way a surgeon is aware of a scalpel that is not yet needed but is part of the choreography. The forum would tell you to keep it out of sight during the set. The phone is the method's umbilical cord, and the method teaches you to cut it while you are working, because the phone reminds you that you are performing, and the performance requires forgetting that you are performing.[otherwise if the player is in the Far End of the Bar]The phone is warm in your pocket. In it: the contacts app waiting, the cursor that will blink in the name field, the ten-digit space the evening has been building toward. You have not looked at it since the set opened. The forum would call this discipline. You are not sure what to call it.[otherwise]The screen is dark. There is nothing on it that matters more than where you are.[end if]"

The bourbon is a thing. The printed name of the bourbon is "bourbon". Understand "bourbon" or "drink" or "glass" or "whiskey" as the bourbon. The description of the bourbon is "Bourbon, neat, in a heavy-bottomed glass that fits the hand the way a good tool fits the hand—not ergonomic exactly, but right. The liquid is the color of dark honey and it catches the lamplight and holds it. You have had two sips. The method says the drink is a prop—a reason to be standing here, something to hold so your hands are not empty, a signal that you are a man at leisure and not a man on a mission. The method may be right about this. The bourbon is also a drink. The bourbon does not know it is a prop. It is the only honest thing you are holding."

The watch is a thing worn by the player. Understand "watch" or "omega" or "seamaster" or "wristwatch" as the watch. The description of the watch is "The Omega Seamaster. Eleven hundred dollars on eBay, from a seller in New Jersey who described it as 'near-mint' and shipped it in a box that smelled faintly of cigarettes. It keeps perfect time. It is not a real Seamaster and it keeps perfect time, and there is something in this that the method understands intuitively—that the performance of a thing and the thing itself are not the same and also not different, that the difference matters and also does not, that you are wearing a fake watch to a real bar to perform a real interaction using a learned method on a real person, and the watch is the most honest object on your body because it is the only one that admits what it is. It says 11:47. Or it says something else. The time does not matter. The time the watch tells is not the time the evening keeps."

The blazer is a thing worn by the player. Understand "blazer" or "jacket" or "coat" or "sport coat" as the blazer. The description of the blazer is "Dark, well-cut, purchased for ninety dollars at a sample sale in the Garment District and tailored for forty more. The method teaches that fit is everything—that a cheap blazer tailored to your body communicates more than an expensive one that does not, that the eye reads silhouette before fabric, that most people cannot tell the difference between a four-hundred-dollar jacket and a four-thousand-dollar jacket but everyone can tell the difference between a jacket that fits and one that doesn't. This is one of the method's true things. You are wearing one of the method's true things and it fits you well and you bought it for nights like tonight and it has been to four bars and a rooftop party and it has never once been the reason anything worked or did not work, but you keep wearing it, because the method says to, because the method needs you to believe that the jacket matters, because if the jacket doesn't matter then maybe the method doesn't matter, and you are not ready for that."

Part Three - The Method

Chapter 1 - Approaching

Section 1 - The Three Second Rule

The three-second rule is a scene. The three-second rule begins when the player is in Bemelmans Bar for the first time. The three-second rule ends when the time since the three-second rule began is 3 minutes.

When the three-second rule begins:
	say "You see her immediately. This is what the training does—it re-wires the entrance. You do not scan the room the way a civilian scans a room, looking for a seat, looking for a friend. You scan for the set. And there it is: a two-set at the bar, one target, one obstacle, no male orbiters, open positioning. HB-eight, maybe eight-five in this light.

You have three seconds. That is the rule. Three seconds between seeing the set and approaching, because after three seconds the hesitation calcifies into something the body remembers, and the body's memory is harder to overwrite than the mind's.

[bracket]The three-second rule is ticking. APPROACH THE SET before it expires, or your confidence will suffer.[close bracket]";
	now the confidence of the player is 6.

When the three-second rule ends:
	if the current action is not opening a set:
		say "The three seconds have passed. Then thirty. Then three minutes. You are still standing near the entrance, holding nothing, performing the universal mime of a man who is [italic type]just looking around[roman type]. Your confidence recalibrates downward. The window is not closed—windows do not close, only your willingness to open them—but the glass is thicker now.";
		decrease the confidence of the player by 2.

Section 2 - Opening the Set

Opening a set is an action applying to nothing. Understand "approach" or "approach them" or "approach the women" or "approach her" or "approach the set" or "approach woman" or "open" or "open set" or "go in" as opening a set. Understand "approach catherine" as opening a set when Catherine is known.

Check opening a set:
	if the player is not in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "There is no one here to approach." instead;
	if the interest of Catherine is greater than 0:
		say "You are already in the set. The approach is behind you." instead.

Carry out opening a set:
	now the interest of Catherine is 1;
	now Catherine is engaged;
	increase the confidence of the player by 1;
	increase the score by 1.

Report opening a set:
	say "You walk over. Not directly to her—never directly to the target. You approach at an angle, addressing the space between them, and you deliver the opener over your shoulder as though it has just occurred to you, as though you were on your way somewhere else and this thought simply needed saying.

'Quick question—settle a debate for me. My friend thinks that people in New York are fundamentally incapable of making new friends after the age of twenty-five. That past a certain point you're just maintaining the ones you already have. He's wrong, right?'

You are looking at [if Margaux is known]Margaux[otherwise]the woman in the green blouse[end if] when you say this. Not at [if Catherine is known]Catherine[otherwise]the dark-haired woman[end if]. The target is the last person you look at. This is counterintuitive. This is the point.

[if Margaux is known]Margaux[otherwise]The woman in green[end if] raises an eyebrow. [if Catherine is known]Catherine[otherwise]The dark-haired woman[end if] turns slightly on her stool."

Chapter 2 - Ordering a Drink

Section 1 - The Order

Ordering a drink is an action applying to nothing. Understand "order" or "order drink" or "order a drink" or "order bourbon" or "get a drink" or "get drink" as ordering a drink.

Check ordering a drink:
	if the player is not in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "There is no bar here. There is no one to pour." instead;
	if the player carries the bourbon:
		say "You have a drink. One is enough. The method says the drink is a prop, not a purpose. Two drinks is a man who came here to drink. One drink is a man who came here to be somewhere." instead.

Carry out ordering a drink:
	say "You catch [if James is known]James's[otherwise]the bartender's[end if] eye—a small nod, nothing more, the minimum viable communication between a man who wants a drink and a man whose life is the providing of drinks. 'Bourbon,' you say. 'Neat.'

The order is minimal because the method teaches that your drink order is a signal: nothing complicated, nothing that requires waiting, nothing that suggests you came here to drink. You came here to work. The bourbon is a prop. The prop is a permission structure—it gives your hands something to do and your presence something to lean on.

[if James is known]James[otherwise]The bartender[end if] pours with the unhurried precision of someone who has poured ten thousand bourbons and will pour ten thousand more. As he reaches for the bottle, a woman three stools down lifts her empty glass. 'James, one more?' she says, and he nods without looking—he has already catalogued her drink, her timing, her pattern—and the nod is a promise that will be kept in its own time.

He sets the glass in front of you on a white napkin that will hold the ring of your drink like a small wet signature, proof you were here.";
	now the player carries the bourbon;
	now James is known.

Section 2 - Sipping

Sipping is an action applying to nothing. Understand "sip" or "sip drink" or "sip bourbon" or "drink" or "drink bourbon" or "take a sip" as sipping.

Check sipping:
	if the player does not carry the bourbon:
		say "You have nothing to drink. The absence of a glass is its own kind of visibility—a man without a drink in a bar is a man without a reason, and men without reasons are noticed." instead.

Carry out sipping:
	say "You take a sip. The bourbon is good—not the best you have ever had, but the best you have had in a room with a gold ceiling, which is a category you did not know existed until tonight. It burns faintly and then the burn becomes warmth, and the warmth is real, the one chemical truth in an evening of constructed ones."

Chapter 3 - Negging

Section 1 - The Neg

Negging is an action applying to one visible thing. Understand "neg [someone]" as negging.

Check negging:
	if the noun is not Catherine:
		say "You do not neg the obstacle. You befriend the obstacle. The obstacle is the door; the neg is the key, and keys only work in the correct lock." instead;
	if the interest of Catherine is 0:
		say "You haven't opened the set yet. The neg before the open is just rudeness—unstructured, unreadable, a stone thrown at a window that has not yet been installed." instead;
	if the warmth of Catherine is less than 2:
		say "She is already cold. Another neg now is not calibration; it is cruelty, and cruelty is the method's shadow, not its substance." instead.

Carry out negging:
	if the perception of Catherine is greater than 6:
		say "'You know, you have this thing where you tilt your head when you're listening—it's like you're evaluating everything, like a little professor. It's kind of—' You pause. The pause is the neg. The word you do not say is the neg. She fills the silence with whatever she is most afraid of, and that is where the space opens.";
		decrease the warmth of Catherine by 1;
		if the attraction of Catherine is invisible:
			now the attraction of Catherine is curious;
		increase the interest of Catherine by 1;
		increase the score by 1;
	otherwise:
		say "'That's a great bag. My sister has the same one.' The delivery is clean but the neg does not land. She smiles politely—the smile of a woman who has received a compliment and does not know it was not one.";
		say "[line break][bracket]The neg must be calibrated to the target's perception. A high-perception target reads subtlety. A low-perception target requires directness. You have miscalibrated.[close bracket]".

Section 2 - The Neg's Aftermath

After negging Catherine:
	if the perception of Margaux is greater than 7:
