Carry out DHV-spiking:
	say "The story comes out of you like something rehearsed that has forgotten it was rehearsed, which is the highest form of rehearsal. You tell them about the time you were in Reykjavik—you were not in Reykjavik for any particular reason, which is itself the first layer of the demonstration, that you are the kind of person who goes to Reykjavik for no reason—and you met a woman who trained Icelandic horses, and she told you that Icelandic horses have a fifth gait that no other breed possesses, called the tölt, and that once you've felt it you can never go back to a four-gaited horse.

You do not explain what this has to do with anything. The absence of the connection is the demonstration. The listener supplies the meaning, and the meaning they supply is always about themselves.

Her head tilts—the thing you noticed earlier, the evaluating tilt. 'I didn't know that,' she says. 'About the horses.'

'Neither did I,' you say. 'Until I was there.'";
