	say "'Come see this,' you say, and you nod toward the far end of the bar where the winter mural is—the one with the rabbit looking at its reflection. 'Have you noticed the rabbit?'

The question is a bridge. It leads from where you are—a man talking to two women at a bar—to where you want to be, which is a man talking to one woman in a quieter corner, which is a man talking to a woman who has chosen to follow him, which is a man who has been chosen, which is what this has always been about: the simulation of being chosen, which, performed skillfully enough, becomes indistinguishable from the thing itself.

Catherine looks at Margaux. Margaux, who is open now, who is warm, who has decided that you are not a threat or at least not the usual kind of threat, gives a small nod—not permission exactly, but the absence of objection, which in the economy of female friendship amounts to the same thing.

Catherine slides off her stool. She brings her drink. You walk together to the far end of the bar, and behind you Margaux watches you go with an expression you will think about later, alone, in the particular silence of a cab at three in the morning.";
