Chapter 8 - The Close

Section 1 - Number Closing

Number-closing is an action applying to one visible thing. Understand "number close [someone]" or "get number" or "get her number" or "close" or "ask for number" or "ask for her number" as number-closing.

Check number-closing:
	if the noun is not Catherine:
		say "You are not trying to close [the noun]." instead;
	if the attraction of Catherine is less than attracted:
		say "She is not ready for the close. A number given before attraction is a number that will not be answered. The phone will ring in her purse and she will look at the screen and she will not remember your face, only the [italic type]shape[roman type] of the interaction, and the shape will feel wrong, and she will let it go to voicemail, and the voicemail will go unheard, and you will become a small unanswered question in someone else's week." instead.

Carry out number-closing:
	say "'I have to go,' you say. The false time constraint—always be the one leaving, never the one staying. 'But we should continue this. The Georgian novelist. I want to hear how it ends.'

You hand her your phone, the contacts screen open, the cursor blinking in the name field. This is the method's final move: the phone handoff, which transfers the act of giving from her to you (you gave the phone) and transforms the number exchange from a request into a collaboration. She is not [italic type]giving you her number[roman type]. She is [italic type]entering her information[roman type]. The frame is everything. The frame is the only thing.

[if the attraction of Catherine is absorbed]She takes the phone. She types. She hands it back, and when your fingers touch around the phone's edge there is a half-second of contact that is not kino, is not technique, is not anything with a name or a place in the sequence. It is just two people's hands touching in a gold room full of rabbits while a man plays Cole Porter and the November dark presses against the windows.

'Catherine,' you read from the screen. You knew this already. But you say it as though you are learning it, because the method's deepest lesson is that you can know something and discover it at the same time, and the discovery is not less real for being engineered.

'The rabbit is still lonely, by the way,' she says. 'You didn't fix that.'

'Next time,' you say.

'Next time,' she says.[otherwise]She takes the phone. She looks at it for a moment—at the blinking cursor, at the small black rectangle waiting to be filled with the ten digits that will or will not change anything—and then she hands it back. Empty.

'I had a nice time talking to you,' she says, and the sentence is a door closing gently, with the lock turned from the inside, and you can hear the click if you listen, and you listen.[end if]";
	if the attraction of Catherine is absorbed:
		increase the score by 3;
		now the player is successfully-closed;
	otherwise:
		say "[line break][bracket]The close has failed. The attraction was insufficient. Review: was the value demonstrated? Was the comfort built? Was the escalation calibrated? The method does not fail. The practitioner fails the method. This is what you will tell yourself in the cab. This is what the method tells you to tell yourself, which is either a kindness or a cruelty depending on what time it is and how much of the night is left.[close bracket]".

Section 2 - The Alternative

Instead of kissing Catherine:
	if the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
		if Margaux is guarded:
			say "You think about leaning in. The thought arrives like a weather system—sudden, atmospheric, irrational. She is right there. The lamplight is doing something to her jaw, her throat, the line where the black dress meets skin. You could just—

No. Her friend is right there. The room is watching. The gold ceiling would see. And the method—the method says the kiss is not a move, it is a consequence. It is what happens after the sequence, not during it. Kissing now would be like playing the last note of a song before the song has started. It would be noise. It would be honest. These are the same thing, and both are fatal.";
			decrease the warmth of Catherine by 1;
		otherwise:
			say "You think about it. The idea surfaces and sits there, warm and dangerous, like a drink you should not order but can feel the shape of in your hand. She is close enough. The angle is right. The room is dim enough to be forgiving.

But this is not that kind of bar. This is not that kind of night. There are things the method accounts for and things it does not, and one of the things it does not account for is the way a room can hold two people in a kind of amber suspension where everything is possible and nothing is yet actual, and to act—to kiss, to close, to [italic type]make it real[roman type]—would collapse the wave function of the evening into a single point, and the point might be yes or it might be no, but either way the beautiful superposition would be over, and the superposition is the only thing tonight that the method did not build.";
	otherwise if the player is in the Far End of the Bar:
		if the attraction of Catherine is absorbed:
			say "The thought arrives and this time it does not leave. She is close. The banquette has done what banquettes do—collapsed the social distance into something intimate, something the body reads as permission even when permission has not been given. Your knee is against her knee. The winter mural watches. The rabbit watches. The piano sounds like a memory of a piano.

You lean in. Slightly. A fraction of a degree. And she does not pull back, which is not the same as leaning forward, but it is not nothing, and in the space between nothing and something the evening holds its breath—

And you stop. You stop because the method did not bring you here to kiss anyone. The method brought you here to close, and the close is a number, and the number is a future, and the future is where you will call her and she will answer and the real thing will begin. The kiss would end the evening. The number continues it. You are choosing the future over the present, which is what the method always chooses, which is maybe what the method is for—a way to keep the present from ever quite arriving.

Or maybe you are afraid. The method does not have a variable for afraid.";
		otherwise:
			say "You think about kissing her and the thought is a miscalibration so severe it almost has a sound—the sound of a wrong note played confidently, the sound of someone reaching for something they have not yet earned, and 'earned' is the method's word but you cannot find a better one, because the method's vocabulary has colonized your own, and the colony does not give back the language it has taken.

She would pull away. You know this. The knowledge is not the method's—the method deals in probabilities, not certainties. The knowledge is yours, the old knowledge, the pre-method knowledge of a man who has been on the wrong side of a lean-in before and remembers the face that met him there: not cruel, not disgusted, just clear. Just no.";
