Chapter 2 - Atmospheric Rules

Every turn when the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
	if a random chance of 1 in 4 succeeds:
		say "[one of]The pianist shifts into a minor key and the room darkens imperceptibly, the way a conversation darkens when someone says something true.[or]A woman at a corner table laughs—a real laugh, surprised out of her, the kind that makes everyone in the room briefly happy without knowing why.[or][if James is known]James[otherwise]The bartender[end if] sets down a drink in front of someone with the gentleness of a man placing a flower on a grave. The drink is amber and catches the gold of the ceiling and for a moment there are two gold things in the world.[or]The door opens and a couple enters, bringing with them a breath of November air that crosses the room like a rumor and is gone.[or]Somewhere in the murals a rabbit stands under a tree. You have been looking at him all night without seeing him. He has been looking at you the same way.[or]The ice in her glass shifts, making the small sound that ice makes when it is thinking about becoming water.[or]A man at a corner table is holding a woman's hand across the white tablecloth. They are not talking. They do not need to be talking. The silence between them is the kind of silence that takes years to build, and watching it feels like looking through a window into a room you have not yet entered and may never enter and are not sure you want to enter, except that you are here, in a different room, running a sequence, and the sequence has no step for what you are feeling right now.[or]The pianist finishes a song. In the three seconds before the next one begins the room holds its breath, and in the held breath you can hear everything—the ice, the murmur, the street outside, the November pressing against the windows like a cat pressing against a door—and then the music starts again and the room exhales and you exhale with it.[or][if Catherine is known]Catherine[otherwise]The dark-haired woman[end if] adjusts the collar of her dress—a small, unconscious motion, the kind of thing a person does when they have forgotten they are being watched. The method has categories for everything she does: the hair tuck is an IOI, the turned shoulder is an IOD, the laugh is a data point. But this—the collar, the slight shiver, the human animal responding to a draft from the door—the method has no name for it. It is just a woman who is cold. And the coldness is hers. And for one moment she is not the target, not the set, not a variable in your equation. She is a person in a room adjusting her collar, and you see it, and the seeing is not strategic, and the non-strategic seeing is the first thing tonight that is entirely yours.[in random order]".

