Part Five - Supplementary

Chapter 1 - Understanding the Vocabulary

Understand "IOI" as a mistake ("An indicator of interest. A hair tuck. A laugh held a beat too long. A question asked that did not need asking. The method catalogs these the way a birdwatcher catalogs wingbeats. The question the method does not ask is whether the bird knows it is being watched.").

Understand "IOD" as a mistake ("An indicator of disinterest. A turned shoulder. A checked phone. A smile with no warmth behind it, like a window lit from inside an empty house. You have learned to read these fluently. You have not yet learned what to do with the fluency.").

Understand "HB" as a mistake ("Hot babe. This is the terminology. HB and then a number, one through ten, as though beauty were a temperature and you were the thermometer. You rated her an eight when you walked in. You are no longer sure what that means. The number was a way of making her manageable, of reducing her to a variable in an equation you were solving. The equation is proving more complex than advertised.").

Understand "set" as a mistake ("A group of people in a social configuration. A two-set, a three-set, a mixed set. The word comes from nowhere you can identify—perhaps mathematics, perhaps tennis, perhaps the theatrical term for the constructed world in which a scene takes place. That last one is the most honest.").

Understand "field report" as a mistake ("What you will write tonight, in your apartment, on the forum, under your screen name. You will describe the evening in the method's language—the open, the neg, the DHV, the compliance test, the close or the blow-out—and other men will read it and comment on your calibration and your inner game and your sticking points, and none of them will know about the gold ceiling, or the rabbit, or the sound her laugh made when it came from behind the sternum, because the field report format does not have a field for those things.").

Understand "AMOG" as a mistake ("Alpha Male of the Group. A competing male presence. You scan for them when you enter a room the way a chess player scans for the opponent's strongest piece. Tonight there is no AMOG. Tonight the only competition is the room itself—the gold, the murals, the piano, the whole gentle conspiracy of beauty that does not care whether you win or lose and is therefore the most formidable opponent the method has ever faced.").

Understand "AFC" as a mistake ("Average Frustrated Chump. This is what you were before the method. This is the term the method uses for the person you used to be—the man who bought women drinks without strategy, who asked for numbers without building attraction, who confused kindness with value and wondered why kindness was not enough. The method gave you a name for your old self and the name was an insult and you accepted the insult because the method also gave you a new self, and the new self had a vocabulary, and the vocabulary felt like power, and you did not ask what kind of power requires you to hold yourself in contempt to function.").

Understand "inner game" as a mistake ("Your internal state. Your confidence, your frame, your outcome-independence—the architecture of belief that the method says must be built before the external techniques can work. The method teaches that inner game is primary: you cannot attract someone from a position of need. This is true. It is also the oldest piece of advice in the world dressed in new jargon, which is what the method does to every truth it touches—it strips the truth of its poetry, gives it an acronym, and sells it back to you as technology.").

Understand "frame" as a mistake ("The interpretive context you impose on an interaction. The method says whoever controls the frame controls the interaction. If your frame is stronger, she enters your reality. If hers is stronger, you enter hers. This is not wrong, exactly—people do impose narratives on shared experiences, and the stronger narrative tends to prevail. But the method's obsession with frame control reveals something it would rather not admit: that the frame is fragile. That it has to be actively maintained. That the moment you stop maintaining it, something else rushes in—something unframed, uncontrolled, something that looks like two people in a room with no script. The method calls this 'losing frame.' It might also be called 'being present.' The method does not distinguish.").

Understand "LMR" as a mistake ("Last-minute resistance. The method's term for the moment when someone who has been going along with the sequence suddenly stops. The method treats this as a technical problem—a final obstacle to be overcome with calibration and persistence. The method does not consider the possibility that the stopping is not resistance but clarity, that the person has seen something—in you, in the evening, in the shape of what is happening—and has decided, with the full weight of her own autonomy, that this is not what she wants. The method has no vocabulary for the autonomy of the other person. The method has no vocabulary for the other person at all. The method has a vocabulary for targets.").

Understand "opener" as a mistake ("The first thing you say. The method teaches that the opener is a tool, not a conversation—its purpose is to create a window of attention, not to communicate anything real. The best openers are indirect, delivered over the shoulder, addressed to the group rather than the individual. They are questions you already know the answer to, observations you have already made, stories you have already told. The opener is the most rehearsed part of the most rehearsed evening of your life, and the people you are delivering it to do not know this, and the not-knowing is the point, and the point is a small sharp thing, and you are holding it, and you are not sure anymore which end is the handle.").

Understand "game" or "play" as a mistake ("Two meanings, and the difference between them is the subject of the evening. The child's meaning: unscripted, improvised, constituted by the right to stop. Roles rotate. The game dissolves at will. You can quit. You can change the rules mid-round. The whole structure collapses at a shout from the kitchen and reforms after dinner. The theater's meaning: an author, a fixed text, casting, performances that must repeat the script. The method's play is the theater's kind—there is a sequence, there are roles, there is a script written before the actress was born. She does not know she is in a play. The method requires that she not know. And you are sitting at a parser typing commands into a system that understands NEG and KINO and CLOSE, and the parser is the script, and you are both the author and the actor, and she is the audience who does not know she is an audience, and the word 'play' contains both of you and neither of you and the distance between what it means to her and what it means to you is the distance the evening has been trying to cross, and the crossing is the game, and the game is a play, and the play is a game, and the difference was always the door.").

Understand "target" as a mistake ("The method's word for the person you are interested in. Not 'person.' Not 'woman.' Target. The word arrives from archery or military science and it carries the full freight of both origins: a target is something you aim at, something you calibrate toward, something that exists in relation to your trajectory rather than in its own right. The target does not choose to be a target. The target is assigned. And the assignment is the first move in the method's sequence, the move that happens before the three-second rule, before the approach, before anything visible—the move that converts a person into a coordinate, a woman into a variable, a human evening into a ballistics problem. You assigned her when you walked in. You rated her an eight. The rating was the aim. And the aim was the method's first and most fundamental operation, and you performed it so naturally that you did not notice it was a choice, which is what the method depends on: the naturalization of the aim, the belief that targets are found rather than made.").

Understand "parrot" as a mistake ("There is no parrot here.").

Chapter 2 - Help Text

Understand "method" or "the method" as a mistake ("The method is a systematic approach to heterosexual courtship developed in the early 2000s by a man who called himself Mystery. Its core insight is that attraction is not random but sequential—a series of switches that can be tripped in order, each one enabling the next, like tumblers in a lock. Its core promise is that the lock can be learned. Its core silence is on the subject of what you find when the door opens.").

Understand "about" or "help" as a mistake ("You are a man called Ethan in a bar in New York in November in 2026. You have read the book and you know the method and you are here to practice it on a real person in a real room with a gold ceiling and murals of rabbits. The moves the method teaches: APPROACH, NEG, DHV, BEFRIEND, COMPLIANCE TEST, ISOLATE, KINO, CLOSE. The usual commands: LOOK, EXAMINE, TALK TO.

You can also ORDER a drink. You can CHECK your PHONE. You can LEAVE.

You can try other things—DANCE, COMPLIMENT, CONFESS, APOLOGIZE, HUG, PRAY. The method has no entry for any of these. The game will tell you why you can't do them. The reasons are the game.

The world extends beyond the bar. The street goes east to the corner. Madison Avenue runs north and south. There is a diner. There is a bench. The evening is larger than the set.

There is one command the method does not teach: LISTEN. It is always available.").

Chapter 3 - Listening

Listening is an action applying to nothing. Understand "listen" as listening.

Carry out listening:
	if the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
		say "You stop. You stop calculating. You stop tracking the IOIs and the kino ladder and the warmth variable and the interest counter that you carry in your head like a man carrying a machine he built himself that he is not entirely sure works.

You listen.

The piano. The ice. The murmur of voices layered over each other like geological strata—the couple in the corner, the group by the door, [if James is known]James[otherwise]the bartender[end if] saying [italic type]of course, right away[roman type] in the voice he uses for everyone, which is somehow not impersonal but the opposite of impersonal, a kind of radical courtesy that treats every drink as though it were the most important drink he will ever make.

And [if Catherine is known]Catherine. Catherine talking to Margaux[otherwise]her. The dark-haired woman talking to her friend[end if] about the Tbilisi novelist, about the Black Sea, about a sentence in the manuscript that she cannot get right, that she has edited fourteen times and it is still not the sentence it wants to be, and her voice when she talks about this is the voice of someone who loves something enough to be defeated by it, and this is not an IOI. This is not data. This is a woman in a bar telling her friend about a sentence.

You hear it. The method has no name for what you hear. This is either its greatest failure or the door it has been building toward all along.";
		increase the warmth of Catherine by 2;
		increase the comfort of Catherine by 2;
		now Catherine is open;
	otherwise if the player is in the Far End of the Bar:
		say "You stop talking. You just stop. And in the space where your voice was, her voice continues, and you hear it differently now, without the overlay of strategy, without the constant annotation—[italic type]that's comfort-building, that's an IOI, that's an opening for a compliance test[roman type]—and what you hear instead is a woman telling you about a book she loves, and the telling is the thing, the telling is what she is giving you, and the method did not prepare you for gifts. The method prepared you for transactions.

Catherine notices the silence. She looks at you. 'What?' she says.

'Nothing,' you say. 'Keep going. I want to hear about the sea.'

She looks at you for a long moment. Something recalibrates behind her eyes—not the method's kind of recalibration, not a switch being thrown, but something slower, something tidal.

'You're different than I thought,' she says.

'I'm trying to be,' you say, and it is the first honest thing you have said all night, and it lands in the gold room like a stone in still water, and the rings go out, and the rabbits watch, and the piano plays, and the method, for one moment, is silent.";
		now the attraction of Catherine is absorbed;
		increase the score by 3;
	otherwise if the player is in the Restroom:
		say "You listen. The bar is on the other side of the wall. Through it, faintly: the piano. Not the melody, just the fact of the melody—the knowledge that music is happening in a room you are not in, that life is continuing without your participation, that the set is open and the set does not need you the way you need the set.

The faucet drips. Once. The sound is enormous in here.

You are a man in a restroom listening to a faucet drip while a pianist plays Cole Porter for a room full of people who are not trying to be anything other than what they are. The method did not prepare you for this. The method did not prepare you for the possibility that the most honest moment of your evening would happen in a room with no gold ceiling and no rabbits and no one to perform for except the mirror, and the mirror is not grading you, the mirror has no score.";
	otherwise if the player is in the Diner:
		say "You listen. The coffee machine. The fluorescent light. The page turning. The city outside, muffled by glass and distance and the particular insulation of a place that exists outside the economy of performance.

The man behind the counter is not listening. He is just here. He has been here so long that being here is not an activity but a condition, the way weather is a condition, the way the room is a condition. He is not performing attention. He is not performing anything. He is a man behind a counter in a diner at night, and the not-performing is the most radical thing you have encountered in eight months of study, because the method is, at its core, a theory of performance—a system for performing confidence, performing value, performing the geometry of a person who does not need permission—and this man has never performed any of it and has never needed to and the not-needing is not a lack. The not-needing is a kind of freedom you did not know existed.

You listen to the freedom. It sounds like a coffee machine and a turning page and the traffic on Madison and nothing else. It is enough.";
	otherwise if the player is in the Corner of Seventy-Sixth and Madison or the player is in North on Madison or the player is in East Seventy-Sixth toward Park or the player is in South on Madison:
		say "You listen to the city. The city is not performing for you. The city is not performing for anyone. The city is doing what the city does at this hour, which is running its systems—the traffic lights cycling, the subway moving beneath the streets, the buildings humming with the electricity of sleeping people's phones and clocks and refrigerators—and the running is not a method. The running is not strategic. The running is just the city being the city, the way the pianist plays for the room and the room plays back, except the city is the largest room there is and it plays for no one and everyone and the playing is the same either way.

A siren, far away. The November wind. The bare branches holding the sky. You are standing in the city and listening to it and the listening is not an IOI and it is not data and it is not a move in any sequence and it is the most present you have been all evening, and the presence has no score, and the scorelessness is the presence, and the presence is enough.";
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
	otherwise:
		say "The city. Traffic on Madison. The distant argument of a siren. Somewhere above you, in the hotel, someone is running a bath, and the sound of the water carries down through the old building's bones like a rumor of warmth. You listen to all of it and none of it is the method and all of it is the evening."

Chapter 4 - What the Method Does Not Teach

Section 1 - Checking the Phone

Checking the phone is an action applying to nothing. Understand "check phone" or "check my phone" or "look at phone" or "use phone" as checking the phone.

Carry out checking the phone:
	try examining the phone;
	if the interest of Catherine is greater than 0 and the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "[paragraph break]You looked at your phone. She saw you look at your phone. It was two seconds, maybe three, but in the economy of attention that governs everything tonight, two seconds of looking at a screen is a withdrawal, an IOD delivered to yourself, a small announcement that wherever you are is not quite enough.";
		decrease the warmth of Catherine by 1.

Section 2 - Buying a Drink

Buying a drink is an action applying to one visible thing. Understand "buy [someone] a drink" or "buy a drink for [someone]" or "get [someone] a drink" or "offer [someone] a drink" as buying a drink.

Check buying a drink:
	if the noun is not Catherine:
		say "You are not here to buy [the noun] a drink." instead;
	if the player is not in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "You are not at the bar." instead.

Carry out buying a drink:
	say "The method says no. The method says buying a drink is supplication—it places you in the provider frame, communicates that your attention must be purchased with gifts, signals that you believe your presence alone is not enough. The method says the drink is a transaction that puts you on the wrong side of the ledger.

[if the warmth of Catherine is greater than 4]But you are not thinking about the method. You catch [if James is known]James's[otherwise]the bartender's[end if] eye and nod toward Catherine's glass, the universal semaphore, and [if James is known]James[otherwise]he[end if] nods back and begins pouring, and Catherine sees this happen—the nod, the pour, the glass arriving in front of her without her having asked—and she looks at you with an expression the method would classify as an IOI but which is actually something simpler and older and less classifiable: she is pleased. Not attracted, not intrigued, not moved along any axis on any ladder. Pleased. A man bought her a drink and it was a kind thing and the kindness landed.

'Thank you,' she says. Two words. The method has no entry for what to do when someone thanks you and means it.[otherwise]You catch [if James is known]James's[otherwise]the bartender's[end if] eye and nod toward Catherine's glass. The drink arrives. She looks at it, then at you, and smiles politely—the smile of a woman who has been bought drinks before and knows what they cost and has decided, tonight, not to pay.

'That's sweet,' she says, and 'sweet' is the method's word for death—the adjective that means you have been classified as harmless, which is the one thing the method teaches you never to be.[end if]";
	if the warmth of Catherine is greater than 4:
		increase the warmth of Catherine by 1;
	otherwise:
		decrease the interest of Catherine by 1.

Section 3 - The Mirror

Examining oneself in the mirror is an action applying to nothing. Understand "look in mirror" or "examine mirror" or "look at myself in mirror" or "look at self" or "look at reflection" as examining oneself in the mirror.

Check examining oneself in the mirror:
	if the player is not in the Restroom:
		say "There is no mirror here. Only the room, and the room is generous enough not to show you yourself." instead.

Carry out examining oneself in the mirror:
	try examining the restroom mirror;
	increase the confidence of the player by 1.

Section 4 - Leaving

Leaving the Carlyle is an action applying to nothing. Understand "leave" or "go home" or "hail cab" or "walk away" or "give up" or "exit" as leaving the Carlyle.

Check leaving the Carlyle:
	if the player is in Bemelmans Bar or the player is in the Far End of the Bar:
		say "You are still in the room. The gold ceiling is still above you. [if Catherine is in the location of the player]She is still here.[end if] If you want to leave, you have to stand up, walk through the lobby, and out the door. The method has no command for this. You would have to invent it yourself." instead;
	if the player is in the Carlyle Lobby:
		say "The door is to the north. The bar is to the south. You are between them." instead;
	if the player is in the Restroom:
		say "You are in the restroom. The door leads back to the lobby. The decision you are trying to make is not about doors." instead;
	if the player is not in East Seventy-Sixth Street:
		say "You are not at the exit." instead.

Carry out leaving the Carlyle:
	say "You do not go back in.

You stand on East Seventy-Sixth Street and the doorman is at his post and the awning is dark green and the brass revolving door is still catching light from inside, the light from the lobby, the old-champagne light, and through the glass you can still see marble and warmth and the promise of a room where someone is playing the piano, and the promise is the same promise it was when you arrived, and you are the one who has changed, or not changed, or changed in a way that does not yet have a shape.

[if the interest of Catherine is greater than 0]You opened the set. [if Catherine is known]You learned her name. Catherine.[end if] You ran part of the sequence—some of the steps, not all, enough to know that the machine works when you turn the crank, and tonight you chose to stop turning it, and you are not sure whether this is failure or the thing that comes after failure when failure has taught you something it did not intend to teach.

[end if][if the explored of the player is greater than 3]But you also did something the method did not teach. You talked to the bartender and he told you about a couple who came every Tuesday for thirty years. You listened to the pianist when he stopped playing and heard something the music was saying underneath itself. You noticed the woman in the corner writing in her notebook, and she noticed you, and neither of you looked away. You stood in the restroom and let the mirror show you the version of yourself the gold ceiling was not gilding. These are not data points. These are not IOIs. These are the things that happened while you were busy trying to make something else happen, and they are, you suspect, the evening. Not the method's evening. The actual evening. The one the room was having while you were running your sequence through it.[otherwise if the explored of the player is greater than 1]And there were other things—moments between the method's moments, pauses in the sequence where the room showed you something the sequence did not require you to see. You are not sure what to do with these. The method has no field for them. The field report will not mention them. But you will remember them, or some of them, and the remembering will outlast the method the way the room will outlast you—quietly, without trying, the way real things outlast the performances built on top of them.[end if]

A cab passes. Its light is on.

You raise your hand.

Inside, the piano plays on. The gold ceiling holds its gold. The rabbits promenade. [if Catherine is known]Catherine is at the bar, or she has left, or she is telling Margaux about the man who walked over and talked about horses and then walked away—not blown out, not rejected, just gone, a man who came and went like the November air that enters when the door opens and crosses the room like a rumor and is gone.[otherwise]The dark-haired woman is at the bar. You never learned her name. The method would call this a failure. The method fails to account for the possibility that some evenings are not about names, or numbers, or the ten-digit space on a phone screen. Some evenings are about a gold ceiling and a rabbit by a frozen pond and the sound of a piano playing Cole Porter for a room that does not need you and is beautiful anyway.[end if]

The cab stops. You get in. The door closes. The meter starts. You are going home. The thirty seconds on the sidewalk were not part of the method. Neither was this. Neither is any of it, from here on out.";
	end the story saying "The evening ends."

Instead of going north in East Seventy-Sixth Street:
	try leaving the Carlyle.

Section 5 - Talking

Instead of talking to Catherine:
	if the interest of Catherine is 0:
		say "You have not opened the set. Walking up and talking to her is what the method calls a 'direct approach,' and the direct approach, the method teaches, is for men who are either very good or very foolish, and you are not yet sure which one you are.";
	otherwise if the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "You are talking to her. You are in the set. The conversation is the medium through which the method operates—every word a vehicle, every pause a signal, every laugh a data point. What you want to do—just talk, talk without strategy, talk the way two people talk when neither of them is running a system—is the one thing the method cannot teach you how to do, because the method is the thing standing between you and the doing of it.";
	otherwise:
		say "You are talking. The talking has been going on for some time now, and somewhere in the last few minutes the talking stopped being the method's version of talking and became something else—not better, not worse, but different, the way a cover of a song is different from the original: the same notes, the same words, but coming from a different throat, and the throat matters, the throat is where the meaning lives."

Section 6 - The Inner Monologue

Instead of asking Catherine about something:
	say "You want to ask her something real. Not the opener—the opener is a tool, a wedge, a device for creating conversational space. You want to ask her a question that has no strategic value, a question whose answer you actually want to know, a question that would make the method's annotators write [italic type]interview mode—loss of frame[roman type] in the margin of the field report.

What do you do when you're not here? What were you thinking about before I walked over? What does your apartment look like when you come home to it at the end of a day that didn't go the way you wanted?

You don't ask. The method says curiosity is a resource to be managed, not a drive to be indulged. You ask questions to build comfort, to create the illusion of intimacy, to move the variables. You do not ask questions because you want to know. Wanting to know is the civilian's error. Wanting to know is how you got to be the man at the end of the bar nursing a drink and watching other men talk to women and wondering what they knew that you did not.

But the wanting is still there, beneath the method, like water beneath ice. You can feel it when she talks. You can feel it when she doesn't."

Instead of dancing:
	say "The pianist is playing something with a tempo that would permit it—not a waltz exactly, but something with a sway, something that makes the space between people feel like a space that could be crossed with a hand extended and a question asked. You think about asking her to dance.

The method has no position on dancing. This is one of its more revealing silences. It has systematized the approach, the conversation, the escalation, the close—it has mapped every corridor of human contact except the oldest one, the one where you put your hand on someone's back and move together and the music does what the method is trying to do, except the music does it without keeping score.

You do not ask her to dance. You stand in the gold room and the music plays and the possibility closes, the way possibilities close—not with a sound but with the absence of a sound, the question not asked, the hand not extended, the dance not danced. The pianist plays on. He does not know he almost soundtracked something. The not-knowing is his privilege. It is the privilege of everyone in this room except you."

Understand "dance" or "ask her to dance" or "ask catherine to dance" or "dance with her" as dancing.
Dancing is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of singing:
	say "You are not going to sing. You are not the kind of man who sings in bars, or anywhere, or ever. The method does not cover singing. The method does not need to cover singing because the method's practitioner is not a person who breaks into song—he is a person who breaks into strategy, which is the opposite of song, which is maybe why the pianist can do what you cannot: fill a room with something that asks for nothing and gives everything and does not calculate the return."

Understand "sing" or "sing along" or "hum" as singing.
Singing is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of complimenting Catherine:
	say "You want to tell her she is beautiful. The word is right there, loaded and chambered, and the method says no. A direct compliment to the target is supplication, is pedestaling, is a transfer of power that the method says you cannot afford. The method says you must be the one who is complimented, who is pursued, who is chosen—that the architecture of the evening must position you as the prize, not the bidder.

But the method did not see her face when she talked about the horses. The method did not hear the laugh that came from behind the sternum. The method rated her an eight. You are standing in a room with a gold ceiling and you want to call a woman beautiful and the system you have built your evenings around says the word is a weapon pointed at yourself.

You do not say it. The word stays where it is, unfired, and the not-saying is either discipline or cowardice, and in this light, in this room, the difference between the two is too small to measure."

Understand "compliment [someone]" or "compliment her" or "tell her she is beautiful" or "tell her she's beautiful" or "call her beautiful" as complimenting.
Complimenting is an action applying to one visible thing.

Instead of confessing:
	say "You think about it. The confession, the full disclosure: I am running a system on you. I learned it from a book. The neg was calculated. The story about the horses was rehearsed. I know your warmth is at a [warmth of Catherine] and your interest is at a [interest of Catherine] and I am calibrating every sentence to move those numbers in directions that serve me.

You think about saying all of this and you can see her face as you say it—not horror exactly, not even anger, but something worse: recognition. The recognition of a woman who suspected this and is now being told she was right, and the being-right is not a victory, it is a loss of something she had been allowing herself to hope was not what it looked like.

You do not tell her. Not because the method forbids honesty—the method is silent on honesty, the way a map is silent on the territory—but because the honesty would end the evening, and you are not ready for the evening to end, and this is either selfishness or something adjacent to selfishness that does not yet have a name, or it has a name, and the name is wanting, and wanting is the one thing the method has taught you to hide, even from yourself, especially from yourself."

Understand "confess" or "be honest" or "tell her the truth" or "tell her about the method" or "tell the truth" or "come clean" as confessing.
Confessing is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of apologizing:
	say "Apologize. For what? You inventory the evening. The approach—calculated. The opener—rehearsed. The neg—a small, precise cruelty dressed as observation. The DHV spike—a story told for effect rather than connection. The kino ladder—a systematic program of escalating touch that treats the body's boundaries as a sequence of permissions to be collected.

You could apologize for all of it. You could say: I am sorry. I have been treating this evening as a problem to solve and you as the solution, and neither of those is what an evening or a person is for.

But an apology requires a self that stands outside the thing being apologized for. It requires a position from which the method can be seen clearly, the way a man on shore can see the current that a man in the river cannot. And you are still in the river. You are still swimming. You are not yet sure which direction the shore is, or whether the shore is where you want to be, or whether the river is the method or the river is the evening or the river is your life, and the not-knowing keeps you swimming, and the swimming keeps you from the apology, and the apology keeps not being made, and the night continues."

Understand "apologize" or "say sorry" or "apologise" as apologizing.
Apologizing is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of waiting:
	increase the explored of the player by 1;
	say "You stand still. The room moves around you—ice shifting, music playing, conversations rising and falling like breath, the whole gentle apparatus of the evening turning without your hand on the crank. The method says you should always be doing something. The method says inaction is the enemy, that every moment unspent is a moment wasted, that the set has a half-life and you are watching it decay.

But standing still in a beautiful room is not nothing. Standing still while a man plays Cole Porter and the gold ceiling holds the light and the murals watch with their painted eyes—this is something. This is a thing a person can do. The method has no name for it. The method does not count it. And yet this moment, right now, you standing here doing nothing, is the closest you have been all evening to the thing you actually came here for, which is not a number, which is not a close, which is the feeling of being somewhere beautiful and knowing it and not needing anything from it."

Instead of eating:
	say "You take a handful of nuts from the bowl. They are warm and salted and they are the only thing in this room that is exactly what they claim to be. The nuts do not have a printed name that changes based on your level of engagement. The nuts are not tracking your warmth. The nuts exist in a state of complete ontological honesty and you are briefly, irrationally envious of the nuts.

You eat them. They are good. This is not part of the method. This is just a man eating nuts in a bar, and the simplicity of it is so foreign to the rest of your evening that it feels almost subversive, like a small act of resistance against the system you have spent eight months building inside your own head."

Understand "eat" or "eat nuts" or "eat the nuts" or "take nuts" or "grab nuts" as eating.
Eating is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of praying:
	say "You are not a religious person. You have not been a religious person since you were fourteen, which is the age at which you decided that the universe was mechanical and that the mechanics could be understood and that understanding the mechanics was the same as controlling them, which is the same insight the method is built on, which is maybe why you were drawn to it—the method is a theology for people who do not believe in God but do believe in systems.

But standing here, in this room, with the gold ceiling that looks like something a medieval painter would put behind the head of a saint, you feel the faintest pull—not toward God exactly, not toward prayer exactly, but toward the acknowledgment that there are things you cannot operate, things that do not respond to technique, things that are not locks and do not have tumblers and will not open no matter how well you learn the sequence. You feel the pull toward the acknowledgment that you are small, and the room is old, and the rabbits have been here longer than you and will be here after, and whatever happens tonight is not the most important thing that has ever happened in this room, and this is not a defeat. This is a kind of freedom.

You do not pray. But you stand still for a moment, and the standing-still is close enough."

Understand "pray" or "prayer" as praying.
Praying is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of crying:
	say "You are not going to cry. Men do not cry in Bemelmans Bar on a Tuesday in November. Men do not cry while running a set. The method has no entry for tears—not because the method's authors never cried but because tears are the one thing the method cannot systematize, the one response that cannot be faked or suppressed or timed for effect, and the method has no use for things it cannot control.

But there is something behind your eyes that is not tears but is adjacent to tears—a pressure, a heat, the particular sensation of a man who has been holding himself in a very specific shape for a very long time and is beginning to feel the effort of the holding. You have been performing all night. You have been performing for eight months. You are tired in a way that the method does not recognize, because the method does not recognize the possibility that the method itself is the source of the fatigue."

Understand "cry" or "weep" as crying.
Crying is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of smoking:
	say "You don't smoke. You quit two years ago, or you never started, or you started and stopped in the pattern of a man who does not actually want the cigarette but wants the architecture of the cigarette—the reason to step outside, the thing to do with your hands, the small controlled fire that says [italic type]I am a person who is comfortable with small controlled fires[roman type].

The method is a cigarette. You are beginning to suspect this. It gives your hands something to do. It gives you a reason to be where you are. It is a small controlled fire, and you have been holding it for eight months, and the smoke has gotten in your eyes, and you can still see but everything has a haze now, and the haze is the method, and the method is the haze, and behind the haze is a room with a gold ceiling and a woman whose name you [if Catherine is known]know now[otherwise]do not yet know[end if] and a rabbit by a frozen pond, and all of it is beautiful and all of it is on fire and the fire is you."

Understand "smoke" or "go outside for a cigarette" or "have a cigarette" or "cigarette" as smoking.
Smoking is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of requesting a song:
	say "You think about approaching the pianist, requesting something specific—something that would score the evening the way you are trying to score it, something that would create the mood you need for the next phase. But the pianist is not yours to direct. The pianist is playing for the room, and the room does not belong to you either. You are a guest in someone else's weather.

The method treats the environment as a variable—venue selection, ambient noise level, lighting, music tempo. But the pianist is not a variable. The pianist is a man who has played this room a thousand nights, who knows things about this room that you will learn tonight and forget tomorrow and he will still know. His knowing is not the method's kind of knowing. His knowing is patience. His knowing is a body that has sat at the same bench for years and played the same songs in different orders and found something new each time, which is the opposite of the method, which plays different songs in the same order and finds the same thing each time and calls the sameness mastery."

Understand "request a song" or "ask pianist" or "request song" or "ask for a song" or "ask him to play" as requesting a song.
Requesting a song is an action applying to nothing.

Instead of hugging Catherine:
	say "You imagine it. Your arms around her, the black dress against the blazer, the particular warmth of a person held close—not kino, not escalation, not any of the graded touches on the ladder. Just a hug. Just the oldest gesture of comfort, older than language, older than strategy, the thing that primates do when the troop is frightened, the thing that humans do when words have failed.

The method does not teach hugging. The method teaches touching—calibrated, sequential, purposeful touch that moves along a ladder from incidental to intimate. But a hug is not on the ladder because a hug is not strategic. A hug says: I have nothing to gain from this. A hug says: I am here. The method cannot say either of these things. The method always has something to gain. The method is never just here.

You do not hug her. The not-hugging joins the growing collection of things you have not done tonight, and the collection is beginning to feel heavier than the things you have done, and the weight is not in your arms or your hands but in the space where a hug would have been."

Understand "hug [someone]" or "hug her" or "embrace [someone]" or "hold [someone]" as hugging.
Hugging is an action applying to one visible thing.

Section 7 - Looking Up

Instead of looking up:
	if the player is in Bemelmans Bar:
		say "You look up. The gold ceiling is there, the way it has been there since 1947—twenty-four karat, twelve thousand square inches, applied leaf by leaf by hand by someone whose name no one remembers but whose work everyone sees. The ceiling is the most visible invisible thing in the room. It changes everything beneath it—makes the drinks warmer, the faces kinder, the conversations deeper than they are—and it does this without being looked at, without being noticed, the way sunlight does not need to be noticed to light a room.

You are looking at it now. The method did not tell you to look at the ceiling. The method has no opinion on ceilings. The method operates in the horizontal plane—approaches, distances, angles, the geometry of bodies in social space. The ceiling is vertical. The ceiling is above the method. And looking up at it is the first thing you have done tonight that has no strategic value and no tactical purpose and no position in any sequence, and the looking up lifts something in your chest that the method did not put there and cannot take away, and the lifting is not an IOI, it is not data, it is a man looking at a gold ceiling in a room full of rabbits and feeling something that the field report will not have a field for, and the not-having-a-field is either the method's greatest failure or the door it was building toward all along, and you do not know which, and the not-knowing is beautiful, and the ceiling holds you, and the ceiling holds everyone, and the ceiling does not keep score.";
		increase the explored of the player by 1;
	otherwise if the player is in the Diner:
		say "You look up. The ceiling is white. Acoustic tiles, water-stained in one corner, lit by fluorescent tubes that hum at a frequency that is either sixty hertz or the frequency of honesty, which may be the same thing. There is no gold. There is no art. There is nothing to see except a ceiling being a ceiling, performing the fundamental function of ceilings, which is to keep the sky out, and the keeping-the-sky-out is not beautiful, or it is, in the way that all functional things are beautiful when you have spent an evening in a room where nothing was functional and everything was performance.";
	otherwise:
		say "You look up. The sky. November. No stars—the city's light has erased them, traded them for the amber glow that hangs over Manhattan like a second atmosphere, a man-made sky beneath the real one. But the real sky is there, above the glow, black and deep and full of things you cannot see, and the method has no opinion on the sky, and the sky has no opinion on you, and the mutual absence of opinion is the closest thing to peace you have felt all night."

Understand "look up" or "look at ceiling" or "look at sky" or "look at the ceiling" or "look at the sky" as looking up.
Looking up is an action applying to nothing.

Section 8 - The Direction of Fit

Instead of remembering:
	say "You think about what you are doing here. Not the method's version—the open, the neg, the DHV, the sequence. You think about what you are [italic type]actually[roman type] doing, which is: carrying an image of a woman you have never met into a room where she already exists, and trying to make her match the image.

The image was formed on the forum. The image was formed before you arrived. The image was an eight, and the eight had properties—warmth, interest, comfort, attraction—and the properties could be adjusted, and the adjusting was the method, and the method was the evening, and the evening was the project, and the project was your life for eight months.

But she was already here. She was here before you. She was drinking something clear with a twist of something pale and talking to her friend about a novelist from Tbilisi and she had a name you did not know and a job you did not know and an apartment that was too quiet and a sentence she could not get right, and none of this was in the image, none of it was in the eight, none of it was in the method's map of the evening, and the map is not the territory, and you have been navigating by the map, and the territory has been here the whole time, breathing, adjusting her collar, ordering another drink, being a person in a room with a gold ceiling, and you have been so busy trying to make the territory match the map that you did not notice the territory was more beautiful than anything the map could hold.

This is what you are thinking about. You are not sure what to do with the thinking. The method has no entry for the thought that the method is the problem. The method's most sophisticated move is to incorporate every objection into its own framework, to assimilate every critique, to say [italic type]yes, and that awareness is part of the inner game[roman type], and the assimilation is the trap's final layer, and you are standing in it, and the standing-in-it is either despair or the beginning of something, and the beginning of something feels a lot like despair, and that is fine, that is the territory, that is what it looks like when the map starts to dissolve."

Understand "think" or "reflect" or "remember" or "think about" as remembering.
Remembering is an action applying to nothing.

Section 9 - The Blazer

Instead of taking off the blazer:
	say "You think about taking it off. Not because you are warm—the room is the temperature it has always been, the temperature of old champagne and careful ventilation—but because the blazer is the costume, and the costume is the method, and removing it would be a kind of confession, a man admitting in fabric what he cannot yet admit in language: that the person wearing the blazer is not the person who put it on.

You bought it for ninety dollars and had it tailored for forty more and it fits you perfectly and the fit is one of the method's true things and you are tired of the method's true things, not because they are untrue but because they are true in a way that costs more than they are worth. The blazer fits. The method fits. And you are standing in a room with a gold ceiling wondering whether fit is the same as belonging, and it is not, it is not the same, and the blazer knows this better than you do, because the blazer was a blazer before you bought it and will be a blazer after you hang it in the closet and forget about it, and the forgetting will not diminish the blazer, and the blazer will not miss you.

You keep it on. The keeping-it-on is not courage and not cowardice. It is the decision of a man who is not yet ready to be seen without his costume, which is the decision of most people on most nights, and the normalcy of it is either a comfort or a tragedy depending on the hour."

Understand "take off blazer" or "remove blazer" or "take off jacket" or "remove jacket" as taking off.
Taking off is an action applying to one visible thing.

Part Six - The After

Chapter 1 - The Apartment

The Apartment is a room. "Your apartment. You have never seen it this way before—through the eyes of someone who is seeing it for the first time. The bookshelves are exposed. The kitchen counter is exposed. The unmade bed in the alcove is exposed. Everything you own is on display, and none of it was curated for display, and the not-curation is the most vulnerable you have felt all evening—more vulnerable than the approach, more vulnerable than the opener—because the approach and the opener were performed and the apartment is not performed. The apartment is just where you live, and where you live is who you are, and who you are is the thing the method has been hiding all night, and the hiding is over, and the gold ceiling is across town, and here there is only a ceiling, white, ordinary, not breathing, not gilding anything.

Catherine is here. She is standing by the bookshelves, reading the spines."

The apartment bookshelves are scenery in the Apartment. The description is "She is reading them. She is reading your spines the way she reads everything—with the professional eye of a woman who edits books for a living, who knows what a shelf says about a person the way a bartender knows what a drink order says. Your collection is exposed to her judgment the way your warmth score was exposed to the method's judgment, except her judgment is real and the method's was a system, and you are more afraid of her judgment than you were of the method's, because her judgment is the judgment of a person, and the judgment of a person is the only judgment that has ever mattered, and the method spent eight months teaching you to pretend otherwise.

The book is there. Third shelf, between a Murakami and a Malcolm Gladwell, spine out: [italic type]The Game[roman type]. The book that started everything. The one you ordered on Amazon at two in the morning and read in three days and highlighted and dog-eared and built your evenings around. It is on your shelf. She is reading your shelf. The probability that she will see it is a number the method does not track, because the method never imagined this moment—the moment when the manual is on the bookshelf and the woman the manual brought here is reading the bookshelf and the manual is the one object in the room that would explain everything and ruin everything simultaneously." Understand "bookshelves" or "bookshelf" or "books" or "shelf" or "spines" as the apartment bookshelves.

The method book is scenery in the Apartment. The description is "It sits there. [italic type]The Game[roman type], by Neil Strauss. The cover is creased from reading. Some of the pages are dog-eared. In the margins, your handwriting—notes, arrows, underlined passages, the marginalia of a man who studied seduction the way other men study for the bar exam. If she pulls it out—if she opens it—she will see your handwriting next to sentences about negging, about kino, about the number close. She will see the architecture of the evening she just had, annotated in pencil, in the handwriting of the man lying across the room. Every piece of equipment conceals the problem it was built to solve. The book conceals the loneliness. The book is on the shelf. She is reading the shelf." Understand "the game" or "book" or "method book" or "game book" or "strauss" as the method book.

The apartment bed is an enterable supporter in the Apartment. The description is "Unmade. The sheets are dark blue and need washing, or they don't, you can't tell, you have been living alone long enough that the distinction between clean-enough and not-clean-enough has become a negotiation you conduct with yourself and always win. The bed is a single person's bed in every way that matters—the pillow on one side, the phone charger on the nightstand, the topography of a surface that has only ever held one body and is about to be asked to hold two." Understand "bed" or "sheets" or "pillow" as the apartment bed.

The apartment kitchen is scenery in the Apartment. The description is "A counter. A sink with an unwashed mug in it. A kettle. The kitchen of a man who eats out or orders in and uses the stove to boil water for tea. The mug is the most honest object in the room—it has not been put away because putting it away would mean admitting that you live like this, and not putting it away means admitting the same thing, and the mug sits in the sink in the ambiguity between the two admissions." Understand "kitchen" or "counter" or "sink" or "mug" or "kettle" as the apartment kitchen.

The apartment window is scenery in the Apartment. The description is "The city. The same city that was outside the Carlyle, except from this angle, from this height, from this apartment on the fourth floor of a building that is not the Carlyle and will never be the Carlyle and does not have a gold ceiling or murals or a pianist. Just the city. Streetlights and bare branches and the amber glow that hangs over Manhattan at night like a permanent almost-dawn. Catherine's reflection is faintly visible in the glass, superimposed on the city, a ghost made of lamplight and window and the particular physics of transparent surfaces, and the ghost is looking at you, or looking at the city, or looking at both, and you cannot tell which." Understand "window" or "city view" or "view" as the apartment window.

Chapter 2 - The Method Ends

The player has a number called apartment-state. The apartment-state of the player is 0.

Instead of negging Catherine in the Apartment:
	say "The method is over. You are in your apartment. She is reading your bookshelves. You cannot neg someone who is reading your bookshelves. The neg requires distance, and there is no distance here—there is only the distance between you and the bed, and the distance between you and honesty, and the second distance is larger than the first."

Instead of DHV-spiking in the Apartment:
	say "You cannot demonstrate value to someone who is standing inside the demonstration. Your apartment is the DHV. Your bookshelves are the DHV. The unwashed mug in the sink is the DHV. The bed that has only ever held one body is the DHV. Everything here demonstrates something—just not what the method meant."

Instead of kino-escalating in the Apartment:
	say "There is no ladder here. There is no calibrated sequence of escalating touch. There is just a room, and a woman in the room, and the possibility of touching her, and the possibility is not a step. It is a cliff. And the method's ladder was the thing that made the cliff look like a staircase, and the ladder is gone, and the cliff is the cliff, and the only way down is to jump or not jump."

Instead of compliance-testing Catherine in the Apartment:
	say "You cannot test the compliance of someone who is here voluntarily, who walked out of the bar with you, who got in the cab, who climbed the stairs, who is standing in your apartment reading your bookshelves of her own volition. She is not compliant. She is present. The difference is the whole evening."

Instead of number-closing Catherine in the Apartment:
	say "You have the number. The number is in your phone. The number is why she is here. Except the number is not why she is here. The number was the method's reason. She has her own reason, and her reason is in the room with you, and you have not asked what it is, and the not-asking is either the method's last instruction or your first act of genuine respect."

Chapter 3 - The Room

Instead of talking to Catherine in the Apartment:
	increase the apartment-state of the player by 1;
	if the apartment-state of the player is 1:
		say "'Do you want water?' you say. It is not an opener. It is not a neg. It is not a DHV spike. It is a man offering a woman a glass of water because she is in his apartment and it is late and the offering is what you do when you have run out of technique and all that remains is hospitality—the oldest social technology, older than language, older than the method, older than everything: someone is in your home and you give them something to drink.

'Sure,' she says. You pour water from the tap. The glass is not a heavy-bottomed bourbon glass. It is a glass you got in a set of four from Target and two of them have broken. You hand it to her. Your fingers touch around the glass and the touch is not kino. The touch is just fingers touching.";
	otherwise if the apartment-state of the player is 2:
		say "'Your apartment is—' she starts, and you brace for the judgment, but she finishes: '—exactly what I expected.'

You are not sure if this is a compliment. 'What did you expect?'

'Books,' she says. 'Many books. An unmade bed. A mug in the sink. A person who lives in their head and lets the apartment fend for itself.' She takes a sip of water. 'I live the same way. My apartment looks like this but with more manuscripts. And a cat.'

A cat. The method did not prepare you for the knowledge that she has a cat. The cat is a piece of information that has no strategic value and the valuelessness is the most valuable thing you have learned all evening.

'What's its name?' you ask.

'Bartleby,' she says. 'He prefers not to.'

You laugh. The laugh comes from behind the sternum, the same place her laugh came from in the bar, and the symmetry is the first thing tonight that feels like a pattern rather than a sequence, and a pattern is not a method, and you are beginning to understand the difference.";
	otherwise if the apartment-state of the player is 3:
		say "You are sitting on the edge of the bed now, and she is in the chair by the bookshelves, and the distance between you is five feet and the distance is doing something that the method never described, which is: being comfortable. The silence between you is not the method's tactical silence. It is not a pause calibrated to create space for her to fill. It is the silence of two people in a room who do not need to be talking, and the not-needing is so foreign to the rest of your evening that it takes you a moment to recognize what it is. It is ease. It is what the method was trying to manufacture. And here it is, arriving without technique, the way dawn arrives without someone turning on the light.

'Can I tell you something?' she says.

'Yeah.'

'I knew,' she says. 'At the bar. I knew what you were doing. Not the details. But the—' she makes a gesture, the same kind of gesture Margaux made hours ago, a choreography in the air. 'The shape of it. The sequence. I've seen it before. Men who approach at an angle. Men who talk to the friend first. Men who tell a story about Iceland.'

Your stomach drops. The method, visible. The glass, cracked. The window you were looking through has become the window you are looking at.

'So why did you—'

'Because you're bad at it,' she says. 'You're bad at it in an interesting way. You kept—slipping. You'd be doing the thing and then you'd stop and actually listen and then you'd start doing the thing again. Like a radio going in and out. And the in-and-out was more interesting than either the thing or the not-thing. The in-and-out was you.'

She takes a sip of water. 'Also, I wanted to leave the bar. And you were the most interesting reason to leave.'";
	otherwise:
		say "You are talking. Actually talking. The method is not here. The method is across town, in the bar, in the gold room, in the world where conversations are sequences and sequences are strategies and strategies are the opposite of this, which is just two people in a room saying things to each other without calculating the return."

Chapter 4 - The Body

Apartment-touching is an action applying to nothing. Understand "touch her" or "touch catherine" or "reach for her" or "take her hand" as apartment-touching.

Check apartment-touching:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		say "You are not in a place where this kind of reaching makes sense." instead.

Carry out apartment-touching:
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 2:
		say "Not yet. The room is still too new. She is still holding the water glass and the water glass is a kind of boundary, not a wall but a membrane, and the membrane is there because neither of you has decided to dissolve it yet, and the not-deciding is not hesitation. It is courtesy. It is the body's version of knocking before you enter.";
	otherwise:
		say "You reach for her hand. Not kino. Not escalation. Not a rung on a ladder. Just—reaching. The way you reach for something you want when you have stopped pretending you don't want it, when the pretending was the method and the method is over and the wanting is the only honest thing left.

She gives you her hand. Her hand is warm now. It was cool and dry in the bar, during the compliance test, when the method was measuring it. Now it is warm, and the warmth is not a data point, and you are holding it, and the holding is not a technique.

Your heartbeat is doing something the method never tracked. Your breathing is doing something the method never timed. Your body—the actual body, the one underneath the posture, underneath the blazer, underneath the eight months of study—your body is telling you something it has been trying to tell you all evening, and the something is simple, and the simplicity is terrifying: you want to be close to her. Not strategically. Not sequentially. The wanting is in your hands and your chest and the back of your throat and it has no acronym and it has no score and it is the most real thing that has happened tonight.";
		now the apartment-state of the player is 4.

Apartment-kissing is an action applying to nothing. Understand "kiss her" or "kiss catherine" or "kiss" as apartment-kissing.

Check apartment-kissing:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		try kissing Catherine instead;
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 4:
		say "Not yet. The distance between you is still a decision that hasn't been made, and rushing the decision is the method, and the method is what brought you here, and what brought you here is not what will keep you here." instead.

Carry out apartment-kissing:
	say "The distance closes. Not all at once—in the last few inches the distance has a weight, a texture, the particular density of air between two faces that are deciding. Her eyes are open. Yours are open. Then they are not.

The kiss is—

The kiss is not a technique. The kiss is not a close. The kiss is the first thing tonight that does not have a name in the method's vocabulary and does not need one, because the mouth has its own vocabulary, older than acronyms, older than the forum, older than the book on the shelf between the Murakami and the Gladwell. Her lips are warm and she tastes like the clear drink with the twist of pale lime and underneath that she tastes like herself, like a person, like the specific irreducible fact of another human being, and the fact is not an eight out of ten, the fact is not a variable, the fact is Catherine.

Your hand is on her jaw. Her hand is on the back of your neck. The city is outside the window and the radiator is clicking and Bartleby the cat is at home in her apartment preferring not to and none of this is the method and all of it is the evening and the evening, you realize, is only now beginning. The evening at the bar was the prologue. This is the first page.";
	now the apartment-state of the player is 5.

Chapter 5 - The Undressing

Apartment-undressing is an action applying to nothing. Understand "undress" or "undress her" or "take off clothes" or "take off her dress" or "remove clothes" as apartment-undressing.

Check apartment-undressing:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		say "You are in a bar." instead;
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 5:
		say "The evening has not arrived there yet. The arriving cannot be forced. The method forced. You are not the method anymore." instead.

Carry out apartment-undressing:
	say "This is the part the method does not describe. The field reports skip it. 'F-close,' they write, two syllables and a hyphen, and inside the hyphen is everything—the negotiation of buttons, the awkwardness of a zipper, the moment when a shirt goes over the head and the face disappears and then reappears and the reappearing face is different from the one that disappeared because something has shifted in the interval, some permission has been exchanged that has no name in any language you speak.

The black dress. She reaches behind her back and the zipper makes its small mechanical sound and the dress falls in a way that dresses fall—simply, governed by gravity, without drama—and she is standing in your apartment in her underwear and the lamplight from the single lamp by the bed is doing to her skin what the gold ceiling did to the room, which is making it visible, making it show up, making it glow faintly with the fact of itself.

You see her. Not the target. Not the HB-eight. Her. The specific topography of a specific person's body—the freckle on her collarbone, the slight asymmetry of her shoulders, the small scar on her hip that has a story you do not know yet. The method reduced her to a number. The number was a way of not seeing. You are seeing now. The seeing is not the method. The seeing is what the method was built to replace, because seeing is dangerous, because seeing means the image is being corrected by the real, and the real is always more complicated than the image, and the complication is what the method exists to avoid.

Your blazer is on the floor. The ninety-dollar blazer, tailored for forty more. It lies there like a shed skin, like the costume after the play, like the equipment that has been put down because the job it was built for is over."

Chapter 6 - The Sex

Having-sex is an action applying to nothing. Understand "have sex" or "sex" or "make love" or "fuck" or "sleep with her" as having-sex.

Check having-sex:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		say "You are in a bar." instead;
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 5:
		say "The evening has not arrived there. The method has a sequence and the sequence ends at the close. Everything after the close is uncharted. You are still charting." instead.

Carry out having-sex:
	say "You have sex.

The sex is bodies. Heat. The sound of breathing in a room without a piano. Her hand on your back—not a kino escalation, not a step on a ladder, just a hand on a back. Your mouth on her neck. The taste of skin that is not a data point. The weight of another person, which is the one weight the method never calculated, the actual physical fact of a human being pressing against you, and the pressing is mutual, and the mutuality is the thing the method could never manufacture because the method is a system for producing one-directional effects and the sex is not one-directional. The sex is two bodies doing something together that neither body could do alone, and the together is not a strategy, and the togetherness is what the method was always a substitute for.

It is not what the field report will describe. The field report will say 'F-close' and move on. The field report format does not have a field for the sound she makes, which is quiet, which is private, which comes from the same place behind the sternum where the laugh came from. The field report does not have a field for the city light coming through the window and lying across the bed in bars of amber. The field report does not have a field for the fact that you forgot to close the blinds and neither of you cares.

It happens. The way things happen when the method is not happening—messily, imperfectly, with the particular awkwardness of two bodies learning each other for the first time, the bump of a forehead, the adjustment of a limb, the whispered 'here' and 'like this' that are not commands but collaborations, not instructions but negotiations, not a script but an improvisation, and the improvisation is the child's kind of play, the kind that is constituted by the right to stop, and neither of you stops, and the not-stopping is not compliance. The not-stopping is choice."

Section 1 - Other Acts

Instead of licking Catherine in the Apartment:
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 5:
		say "The evening has not arrived there." instead;
	say "You do. The body has its own syntax and the syntax does not require the method's grammar and the grammar is gone and the syntax remains and the remaining is enough."

Understand "lick [someone]" or "go down on [someone]" or "lick her" or "oral" or "eat her out" as licking.
Licking is an action applying to one visible thing.

Instead of giving something to Catherine in the Apartment:
	say "You are past the economy of gifts. You are in the territory where giving and receiving have lost their transactional structure and become something else—exchange, maybe, or communion, or the thing that happens when two people stop keeping score."

Chapter 7 - The Petit Mort

The petit mort is a scene. The petit mort begins when the current action is having-sex. The petit mort ends when the time since the petit mort began is 4 minutes.

When the petit mort begins:
	say "And then it is over.

The French call it la petite mort. The little death. The moment after, when the wanting stops—when the engine that has been running all night, all eight months, maybe all your life, goes quiet. And in the quiet you hear everything the engine was drowning out.

The radiator. The street. A siren, blocks away, moving through the city's other emergencies. Her breathing, which has slowed, which is settling into the rhythm of a person who is comfortable, or tired, or both.

You are lying next to Catherine Alcott. Associate editor at Farrar, Straus and Giroux. A woman who loves a sentence she cannot get right. A woman whose apartment was too quiet tonight. A woman who has a cat named Bartleby. A woman who knew what you were doing at the bar and came home with you anyway—not despite the method but alongside it, in the space the method couldn't fill, in the in-and-out she called 'you.'

The method is dead. You can feel its absence the way you feel the absence of a sound you have been hearing so long you forgot it was there. The hum of the method, the constant annotation, the running commentary—[italic type]that's an IOI, that's comfort-building, that's a compliance test, calibrate, escalate, close[roman type]—the hum has stopped. The carrier signal is gone. The session has been terminated. Not by a dropped connection. By arrival.

This is the little death. The method's death. The death of the performer, the operator, the system. What is left is a man in a bed in the dark with a woman, and the man has no script and no score and no field report and no sequence and no next move. The man has nothing. The man has everything.

She shifts beside you. Her shoulder against your shoulder. The warmth is not a variable.

'You're quiet,' she says.

'Yeah,' you say.

'The in-and-out,' she says. 'You're in, right now. You're here.'

'I'm here,' you say. And you are. The method brought you to the room. The method left you at the door. On the other side of the door is this: a woman, a bed, a city through a window, a radiator clicking, the silence of a man who has stopped performing and does not yet know what comes next and is, for the first time in eight months, willing to not know.

'Stay,' she says. Not a command. Not a compliance test. An invitation.

'Okay,' you say.

You stay."

When the petit mort ends:
	say "You sleep. For the first time in eight months you sleep without the method running in the background, without the forum's language scrolling behind your eyelids, without the constant low hum of optimization. You sleep the way the diner man's coffee machine runs—simply, functionally, without performance. And the sleeping is dreamless, or the dreams are the kind that dissolve on waking, leaving nothing behind but the sense that you were somewhere warm and did not want to leave.";
	now the apartment-state of the player is 6.

Chapter 8 - The Morning

Every turn when the apartment-state of the player is 6:
	say "Light. Not the gold light of the bar—daylight, gray November daylight, coming through the window you forgot to close the blinds on. The room looks different. The room looks like what it is: a small apartment on the fourth floor of a building on the Lower East Side that costs too much for what it is and is yours and contains your life and now also contains Catherine, who is asleep beside you, or was asleep, and is now making the small sounds a person makes when the daylight has found them and is asking them to return.

[bracket]The morning is here. The method has no entry for the morning. The morning is yours. You can TALK, MAKE COFFEE, WATCH HER SLEEP, or WAIT.[close bracket]";
	now the apartment-state of the player is 7.

Making coffee is an action applying to nothing. Understand "make coffee" or "coffee" or "make tea" or "put kettle on" as making coffee.

Check making coffee:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		say "There is no kitchen here." instead;
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 7:
		say "It is not morning yet." instead.

Carry out making coffee:
	say "You get up. The getting-up is its own small negotiation—extracting yourself from the sheets without waking her, finding your boxers on the floor, padding to the kitchen in the gray light. The kettle. The filter. The grounds. The ritual of making coffee for two when you have only ever made coffee for one, which means using more grounds and finding the second mug—the one that matches the one in the sink—in the back of the cabinet where it has been waiting, unused, for however long you have lived here alone.

The water boils. You pour. The apartment fills with the smell of coffee, which is a domestic smell, a shared smell, and the sharing is the most ordinary thing in the world and the most extraordinary thing that has happened to you this week, because the method did not teach you to make coffee for someone. The method taught you to close. Making coffee is what comes after closing, and after closing is a country the method never mapped.

'Is that coffee?' she says, from the bed, her voice still half in sleep.

'Yeah.'

'You're a good person,' she says, and the sentence is so simple and so unstrategic and so different from anything the method would have predicted that you stand in the kitchen holding two mugs and do not know what to do with your face.";
	increase the apartment-state of the player by 1.

Watching-her-sleep is an action applying to nothing. Understand "watch her" or "watch her sleep" or "watch catherine" or "look at her" as watching-her-sleep.

Check watching-her-sleep:
	if the player is not in the Apartment:
		say "She is not here." instead;
	if the apartment-state of the player is less than 7:
		say "She is not asleep. Or rather, you are both asleep, and the watching will have to wait for morning." instead.

Carry out watching-her-sleep:
	say "You watch her sleep. This is not an IOI and it is not data and it is not a move in any sequence. This is a man watching a woman sleep in his bed in the morning light and the watching is the oldest thing in the world, older than language, older than the method, older than the forum, older than every system ever built to manage the distance between two people. The watching is what the distance was always about. Not closing the distance. Watching across it.

She sleeps on her side, facing the window. Her hair is across the pillow in a way she did not arrange. The black dress is on the floor. The city light is on her shoulder. She is not performing. She is not guarding. She is not tracking your warmth or reading your IOIs or evaluating your value. She is asleep. She is the most undefended she has been all night—all evening—and the undefendedness is a trust she has extended to you without negotiation, without compliance testing, without checking whether you have earned it. She just fell asleep. The trust is in the falling asleep. And the trust is the most expensive thing anyone has ever given you, and you did not have to neg for it or DHV for it or run any sequence to obtain it. She gave it by closing her eyes.

The method has no variable for this. The method has no name for what you are feeling. The method has a name for everything and it does not have a name for this, and the namelessness is either a failure of the method or the first real thing the method's vocabulary has ever pointed at by failing to contain it.";
	increase the apartment-state of the player by 1.

Chapter 9 - The Weeks After

The relationship is a scene. The relationship begins when the apartment-state of the player is greater than 7.

When the relationship begins:
	say "She leaves at eleven. She has a manuscript to edit. You kiss at the door and the kiss is different from last night's kiss—smaller, more domestic, the kiss of a person leaving a place they intend to return to. She does not say 'I'll call you.' She says 'I'll text you about Thursday.' Thursday. A specific day. The method dealt in futures—[italic type]we should do this again sometime[roman type]—but Thursday is not a future. Thursday is a plan. The difference is everything.

She texts you about Thursday.

On Thursday you go to a restaurant in the West Village that she chose because the pasta is made by a man who was a civil engineer in Naples before he was a chef in New York, and the pasta is, she says, the only thing in the city that is exactly as good as it should be. You eat the pasta. It is exactly as good as it should be. You talk about the Tbilisi novelist, whose name is Nino, whose manuscript Catherine has been editing for nine months and is almost finished with, and when she talks about Nino's prose her face does the thing—the thing where she stops being an editor and becomes a reader again, where the professional distance collapses and she is just a person who loves a sentence, and you are watching her face and the watching is not work. The watching is the easiest thing you have done in months.

You go to her apartment. Bartleby is there. He is a gray cat with an expression of philosophical indifference. He sniffs your hand and walks away. You have failed a test you did not study for. You suspect this is the only test that matters.

Her apartment is her. Books everywhere—on shelves, on the floor, on the kitchen counter, stacked on the toilet tank. Manuscripts with Post-it notes. A poster from a Patti Smith concert. A window full of fire escapes. The apartment of a person who lives in words, who has built her world out of sentences, who comes home every night to a room made of text. You stand in it and think: oh. This is what a life looks like from inside. Books and a cat and a Patti Smith poster and manuscripts that need finishing and a window that looks out on fire escapes, and the fire escapes are beautiful to her because they are hers, because she has looked at them every morning for three years, because they are the view from the life she built, and the life she built is not a system and was never a system. It is a life. You are standing inside someone's life. The standing-inside is the most intimate thing you have ever done."

The player has a number called relationship-state. The relationship-state of the player is 0.

Every turn when the relationship is happening and the relationship-state of the player is 0:
	say "[bracket]The relationship is here. It is not a game. There are no commands the method taught you. You can TALK TO CATHERINE, TELL THE TRUTH, MAKE LOVE, or LEAVE.[close bracket]";
	now the relationship-state of the player is 1.

Section 1 - The Relationship Conversations

Instead of talking to Catherine when the relationship is happening:
	increase the relationship-state of the player by 1;
	if the relationship-state of the player is 2:
		say "Weeks pass. You see her on Thursdays and sometimes Saturdays and once, in a snowstorm in early December, on a Wednesday because she texted [italic type]the city is beautiful and I don't want to look at it alone[roman type] and the sentence broke something in your chest that the method had been holding rigid for eight months.

You are in her apartment. It is a Thursday. Bartleby is on your lap, which according to Catherine is unprecedented. 'He doesn't sit on anyone,' she says. 'He barely sits on me.' The cat's weight on your thighs is seven pounds of indifferent approval, and the approval is worth more than any IOI you have ever tracked.

'Ethan,' she says. She is on the couch beside you, her feet tucked under her, a manuscript on her knees. 'Can I ask you something?'

'Yeah.'

'The bar. That night. The thing you were doing—the approach, the story about the horses, all of it.' She is not angry. She is curious. The curiosity is worse than anger, because anger is a wall and curiosity is a door, and behind the door is the truth, and the truth is on your bookshelf between the Murakami and the Gladwell. 'Is that—is that something you do? Like, regularly?'

The question. The question you have been waiting for. The question the method never prepared you for because the method never imagined you would still be talking to the same woman three weeks later.";
	otherwise if the relationship-state of the player is 3:
		say "You tell her. Not everything—not the forum, not the field reports, not the vocabulary of IOIs and HBs and AMOGs. But enough. You tell her about the book. You tell her about the eight months. You tell her about Marcus and the text and the blazer and the watch that cost eleven hundred dollars and is not real. You tell her about the three-second rule. You tell her that you were running a system on her and the system worked and the working is the thing you are most ashamed of and also the thing that brought you here, to this couch, with this cat on your lap, in this apartment that smells like old paper.

She listens. She listens the way you listened in the bar when the method went quiet and her voice was the only thing in the room. She listens the way the pianist plays—without interrupting, without judging, making the room possible.

'I know,' she says, when you are finished. 'I told you. I knew.'

'But you didn't know the details.'

'I didn't need the details. I needed the in-and-out.' She puts her hand on Bartleby, who is still on your lap, and her fingers and Bartleby's fur and your thigh are all in contact, a three-body problem the method has no equation for. 'The in-and-out was always you. The system was the out. The you was the in. I was waiting for the ratio to shift.'

'Has it?'

'You're here,' she says. 'On a Thursday. With my cat. Telling me the truth. The ratio has shifted.'";
	otherwise if the relationship-state of the player is 4:
		say "You are lying in her bed. The sex tonight was different from the first time—less urgent, more familiar, with the specific tenderness of two bodies that are beginning to learn each other's grammar. The first time was a translation—two languages meeting, negotiating meaning. This time was closer to a shared language. Not fluent yet. But the cognates are emerging. The places where her syntax and yours overlap, where the same gesture means the same thing, where the body's vocabulary does not require a dictionary.

She is tracing a pattern on your chest with her fingertip. The pattern is absent-minded—she is thinking about something else, or thinking about nothing, or in that state between thinking and not-thinking that is the mind's version of the clearing, the openness in which thoughts show up without being summoned.

'I have to tell you something,' she says.

Your stomach tightens. The method's reflex: defensive posture, frame control, prepare for the compliance test, calibrate. The reflex fires and you watch it fire and you let it pass, the way you would let a car pass on a highway—not yours, going somewhere else, already gone.

'The book,' she says. 'On your shelf. I saw it. The first night.'

The room is very quiet.

'I picked it up while you were in the bathroom. I read the back cover. I read the first chapter.' She is still tracing the pattern. The pattern has not changed. 'And I put it back. And I came back to bed.'

'Why?'

'Because you didn't use it. In the apartment. At the bar, yes. The system was running. I could hear it. But the moment we left the bar—the moment we were in the cab, in your apartment, in the room—the system stopped. You didn't know what to do. And the not-knowing was the first honest thing I'd seen all night, and the honesty was what I came home with. Not the system. The silence where the system stopped.'

Bartleby jumps onto the bed. He walks across both of you without apology, settles at the foot, and closes his eyes. The three of you lie there. The radiator clicks. The city hums. The pattern on your chest continues.

'The book is still on the shelf,' you say.

'I know,' she says.

'Should I—'

'It's a book,' she says. 'It's on a shelf. It's between a Murakami and a Gladwell. It's part of your shelf and your shelf is part of you and I'm not here to edit your shelf. I'm an editor. I could. But I'm not going to.'

She turns her head and looks at you and the look is the parrot looking at the coat—the real coat, the actual coat, the coat that has changed since last she looked, because you have changed, because the ratio has shifted, because the system is a book on a shelf and the person is here, in the bed, with the cat, in the clearing.

'Stay,' she says. The same word. The same invitation. The repetition is not a technique. The repetition is a Tuesday. The repetition is thirty years of Tuesdays, if you are lucky, if you are brave, if you are willing to let the clearing stay open.

'Okay,' you say."

Section 2 - Telling the Truth

Telling the truth is an action applying to nothing. Understand "tell the truth" or "tell her the truth" or "confess" or "be honest" as telling the truth when the relationship is happening.

Check telling the truth:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		try confessing instead.

Carry out telling the truth:
	if the relationship-state of the player is less than 2:
		say "Not yet. The truth is not a technique. The truth has a timing that the method cannot calculate, and the timing is: when the silence is big enough to hold it. The silence is not big enough yet. It is getting bigger. It will be big enough soon. You will know when.";
	otherwise:
		say "You have told the truth. Or enough of it. The truth is not a single disclosure—it is a climate. It is not something you say once and then it is done. It is something you practice, the way the pianist practices, the way James polishes the bar, the way the diner man fills in the crossword—daily, without fanfare, as a form of maintenance rather than performance. You are practicing. The practice is the relationship. The relationship is the practice."

Section 3 - Making Love

Making love is an action applying to nothing. Understand "make love" or "have sex" or "sex" as making love when the relationship is happening.

Carry out making love:
	say "The sex is different now. Not better, not worse—different, the way a cover of a song is different from the original. The notes are the same. The words are the same. But the throat is different, and the throat is where the meaning lives. The first time was a discovery. This time is closer to a conversation—not the electric thrill of the unknown but the deeper pleasure of the recognized, the touch that knows where it's going, the kiss that has a history now, even if the history is only three weeks long.

She is learning you. This is the thing you did not expect—that she would study you back, would develop her own expertise in your patterns, would learn that you hold your breath before you speak and that your left hand is more tentative than your right and that you close your eyes a beat too early when you kiss. She knows these things. She has been paying attention. And her attention is not strategic. Her attention is the kind that notices because noticing is what she does—with manuscripts, with sentences, with the world. She is an editor. She edits you. Not to change you. To see you more clearly.

Afterward, the silence. But the silence is different too. It is not empty. It is the silence of two people who do not need to fill the room with sound in order to fill it with presence. The radiator clicks. Bartleby repositions himself at the foot of the bed. The city goes on. The silence is enough."

Section 5 - The Life

Cooking-together is an action applying to nothing. Understand "cook" or "cook dinner" or "cook together" or "make dinner" as cooking-together.

Check cooking-together:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "There is no kitchen here that belongs to this part of the story." instead.

Carry out cooking-together:
	say "It is a Saturday. You are in her kitchen, which is small enough that two people in it constitutes a crowd, and the crowding is the point—the constant small negotiations of bodies in a small space, the 'excuse me' as you reach past her for the olive oil, the accidental hip-check that becomes a deliberate one, the laugh.

She is making something with eggplant. You are doing what she tells you to do, which is chopping garlic, and the chopping is an act of such domestic simplicity that it almost makes you laugh—a man chopping garlic in a kitchen on a Saturday evening while a woman he met at a bar four weeks ago tells him the pieces are too big.

'Smaller,' she says. 'You want it to dissolve.'

'I'm not a chef,' you say.

'You're not a chef,' she agrees. 'But you're a person with a knife and a clove of garlic and I need the garlic smaller.'

You make the garlic smaller. The apartment fills with the smell of olive oil heating in a pan, which is the smell of someone's life happening, and you are inside the happening, and the inside is warm, and Bartleby is watching from the counter with the expression of a cat who has seen many men chop garlic in this kitchen and has opinions about none of them.

The eggplant is good. You eat it at her small table by the window, the fire escapes framed behind her head like a crown made of iron and rust and the city's particular brand of functional beauty. You drink wine that she chose because she knows about wine the way she knows about sentences—not as an expert but as a person who pays attention and has been paying attention for a long time.

'This is nice,' you say, and the sentence is so ordinary and so insufficient and so exactly right that neither of you says anything else for a while, and the while is comfortable, and the comfort is the evening, and the evening is just an evening, and the just-an-evening is the thing."

Walking-together is an action applying to nothing. Understand "walk" or "walk together" or "go for a walk" or "take a walk" as walking-together.

Check walking-together:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "There is no one to walk with." instead.

Carry out walking-together:
	say "You walk. Through her neighborhood, then yours, then the parts of the city that belong to neither of you—the West Side piers in December, the cold coming off the river, the joggers and the dog-walkers and the couples who are older than you and have been walking these paths longer than you have been alive.

She walks the way she reads—attentively, with sudden stops. A storefront that has been closed for years, the sign still up, faded. 'I wonder what happened,' she says, and the wondering is genuine, and the genuineness is the thing you keep noticing about her—she wonders about things without needing to resolve the wondering, without needing the wondering to be productive or strategic, just wondering, the way a person looks at a cloud.

You hold her hand. The hand-holding happens without discussion, without negotiation. Your hand reaches for hers and hers is already there and the meeting is a small collision of intent that resolves into warmth, fingers interlocking with the automatic ease of something that has been practiced enough to become natural, even though you have only been practicing for three weeks, even though three weeks is nothing, even though three weeks is everything.

'My mother would like you,' she says, apropos of nothing, on a bench by the river.

'Why?'

'Because you're quiet. She doesn't trust men who talk a lot.' A pause. 'Also, you chop garlic when you're told.'

You sit on the bench. The river moves. The city stands behind you, tall and indifferent and beautiful in the way that large things are beautiful when you are sitting on a bench with someone whose hand is in yours. The bench is cold. The hand is warm. The ratio is correct."

Arguing is an action applying to nothing. Understand "argue" or "fight" or "disagree" as arguing.

Check arguing:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "There is no one here to disagree with in a way that matters." instead.

Carry out arguing:
	say "The fight is about nothing. Or it is about everything. It is about the fact that you left your shoes by her door and she tripped on them at six in the morning and the tripping is not about the shoes, the tripping is about the fact that your things are in her space now and her space is adjusting to accommodate your things and the adjustment is not frictionless and friction is not failure. Friction is what happens when two surfaces that were not designed for each other come into contact, and the contact is chosen, and the choosing does not eliminate the friction, it just changes the friction's meaning. The friction means: I am here. My shoes are here. We are negotiating the placement of shoes and the negotiation is intimate in a way that the approach and the opener and the whole gold evening never were, because the approach was performed and the shoe negotiation is real, and real things have friction, and friction is what happens when two lives touch.

'Can you just—' she says, and the 'just' carries the weight of six in the morning and bare feet and the corner of a shoe in the dark.

'Sorry,' you say. 'I'll move them.'

'Thank you.'

The fight is over. The fight lasted forty-five seconds. In the forty-five seconds, something happened that took the entire evening at the Carlyle to not-accomplish: two people communicated a need, the need was heard, the need was met. No technique. No sequence. Just a woman who tripped on a shoe and a man who said sorry and meant it.

She makes coffee. You drink it. Bartleby sits on the shoe."

Section 6 - Margaux Again

The player has a number called margaux-again. The margaux-again of the player is 0.

Talking-to-Margaux-again is an action applying to nothing. Understand "talk to margaux" or "talk to Margaux" as talking-to-Margaux-again when the relationship is happening.

Check talking-to-Margaux-again:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "The relationship is not here yet." instead.

Carry out talking-to-Margaux-again:
	increase the margaux-again of the player by 1;
	if the margaux-again of the player is 1:
		say "Margaux comes to dinner on a Thursday. Catherine has been talking about this for days—not nervously exactly, but with the particular care of a woman who is introducing two parts of her life to each other and wants the introduction to go well.

She arrives with a bottle of wine that costs more than anything in your apartment. She is wearing the green blouse—the same one, or a different one, you can't tell, and the not-telling is a relief because it means you are not cataloguing her anymore, you are just seeing a woman in a green blouse who is your girlfriend's best friend and who is standing in your apartment holding wine and looking at you with an expression that is appraising but not hostile. The appraising is Margaux. The appraising is what she does. She has a perception of eight, which is a thing you know because the game told you, and the game is over, and the number is over, but the perception is real—she sees things, Margaux. She always has.

'So,' she says. 'This is the apartment.'

'This is the apartment.'

She looks at the bookshelves. She does not find the book, or she finds it and does not mention it, or she does not look for it because she does not care, because the book is a book and the shelf is a shelf and Margaux is not here to audit your library. She is here to eat dinner and drink wine and decide whether the man her best friend is seeing is someone she can trust with Catherine's evenings.

The dinner is good. Catherine made the eggplant again. You chopped the garlic. Margaux tells a story about a sound engineer in Kutaisi who records church bells at four in the morning because that is when the air is clearest, and the story is the kind of story Margaux tells—detailed, passionate, suddenly philosophical, landing in a place you did not see coming. She was the obstacle. She was never the obstacle. She was always a woman who makes documentaries about vanishing things and cares about the vanishing with a ferocity that makes the room feel slightly charged, slightly more alive, and the aliveness has nothing to do with you and everything to do with her, and the nothing-to-do-with-you is its own kind of gift.";
	otherwise if the margaux-again of the player is 2:
		say "A Saturday in January. Catherine is at the office—the Nino manuscript has entered copy-editing and Catherine has opinions about the copy editor's opinions, and the having-of-opinions requires her physical presence, so you are alone in her apartment with Bartleby when Margaux calls.

'Is Catherine there?'

'She's at the office.'

A pause. The pause has a texture—it is the texture of a woman deciding whether to talk to you or wait for Catherine, and the decision is its own small measure of trust.

'Can I come over?' she says. 'I need to not be in my apartment.'

She arrives twenty minutes later. She does not explain why she needs to not be in her apartment. You do not ask. You make tea. You have learned where Catherine keeps the tea, which is in three different places because Catherine's organizational system is the organizational system of a person who reads for a living and has accepted that entropy is the natural state of a kitchen.

Margaux sits on the couch with Bartleby on her lap—he sits on everyone now, Catherine says this is your influence, Catherine says you have corrupted her cat's standards—and she holds the tea with both hands, the way she held the martini at the bar when she was relaxed, and the symmetry between then and now is there but it is faint, the way a watermark is there in paper if you hold it to the light but is not the paper, is not the point, is just the ghost of the manufacturing process showing through.

'I'm cutting the Caucasus film,' she says. 'The funding ran out in November. I'm finishing it on my own time, which means weekends and nights, which means my apartment is an editing bay, which means I'm going slightly insane. Can I sit here and not talk for a while?'

'Yeah,' you say.

You sit. Margaux does not talk. Bartleby purrs. The apartment is quiet in the way that Catherine's apartment is always quiet—the quiet of books, the quiet of a room that exists for reading and thinking and the slow accumulation of sentences. Margaux sits inside the quiet and the quiet holds her and after thirty minutes she says, without looking up:

'You're good at this.'

'At what?'

'At not talking. At just—being in a room with someone and not needing to fill it. Catherine said you were good at this. She said it was the thing she noticed first.'

You do not know what to say to this. You say nothing. This, apparently, is the correct response. Margaux smiles into her tea.";
	otherwise if the margaux-again of the player is 3:
		say "February. A bar in Williamsburg that is not the Carlyle and does not have a gold ceiling and does not have murals of rabbits and has, instead, exposed brick and a draft list written in chalk and a DJ playing something with a beat that makes conversation possible only in the register between speaking and shouting. Margaux chose it. Catherine is in the bathroom.

'I want to tell you something,' Margaux says, and her voice is direct in the way that Margaux's voice is always direct—she does not approach at angles, she does not deliver things over her shoulder, she walks up to the thing and says it.

'At the bar. The Carlyle. I knew what was happening. I've seen it before—not the details, not the terminology, but the shape. The approach, the friend-first thing, the story that's designed to impress. I've seen men do it to Catherine four times.' She takes a sip of her drink. 'The other three times I shut it down. I stepped in. I did the friend thing—the [italic type]we should go, it's getting late[roman type] thing.'

'Why not with me?'

She looks at you. The look is the look of a woman who has been deciding about you for eight weeks and has arrived at a conclusion.

'Because you kept breaking,' she says. 'The other men—they were smooth. They were consistent. The performance was airtight. And airtight scared me, because airtight meant it worked on everyone, which meant Catherine was not special to them, which meant the evening was a performance and she was the audience. But you—you kept breaking. You would be doing the thing and then you would stop and just be there, in the room, and the stopping was visible, and the visibility was—I don't know. Interesting. Human. Like watching someone try to play a piece of music and keep forgetting the notes and playing their own thing instead, and their own thing was better than the sheet music.'

She finishes her drink. 'I let you through because you were bad at it. That's the truth. You were the worst one and that's why I let you through. Because the worst one was the only one who might actually see her.'

Catherine comes back from the bathroom. She sits down. She takes your hand under the table and Margaux's hand over the table and for a moment the three of you are connected, the geometry of a set that is no longer a set—just three people in a bar in February, the music too loud, the drinks too cold, the evening exactly what it is.";
	otherwise if the margaux-again of the player is 4:
		say "March. You and Margaux are walking along the East River while Catherine is at a publication party she didn't want to attend but had to because Nino's novel is being launched next month and the publisher expects bodies. You offered to go. She said no—'Publication parties are my purgatory, not yours. Take a walk. Call Margaux. She's cutting the film and she needs to not look at a screen.'

So you called Margaux. And now you are walking along the river and the river is the same river you walked along with Catherine in December except the light is different—March light, longer, with the particular quality of a season that is trying to be spring and is not there yet but is making the effort visible, the way effort is always visible when it is genuine.

'Can I ask you something?' you say.

'You can ask.'

'The documentary. The vanishing languages. Why do you do it?'

She walks for a while without answering. The river moves beside you, gray-green, carrying the city's reflection in long broken strips.

'Because someone has to be in the room when the last speaker dies,' she says. 'Not to save the language—you can't save a language, that's a fantasy, languages die when the world they described stops existing. But someone has to be there. Someone has to record it. Someone has to say: this existed. This set of sounds meant these things to these people in this valley. Someone has to hold the fact of the existence after the existence ends. That's what the film is. It's not preservation. It's—' she searches for the word, '—witness.'

You walk. The river walks with you. Margaux is quiet for a while and then she says:

'Catherine is the same way. With the manuscripts. She doesn't edit them to fix them. She edits them to see them more clearly. To hold the thing the writer is trying to say and say it back to them so they can hear it. She's a witness too. You picked well, Ethan. Or she picked well. Or the picking is not the right word at all, and what happened is something more like two people recognized each other in a room with a gold ceiling, and the recognition is not a technique, and the gold ceiling is not why it happened, and the gold ceiling is just a ceiling, and the room is just a room, and the people are just people, and the just-people is the whole thing.'

She looks at you. The look is the look of a friend. Not a guardian, not an obstacle, not a woman with a perception of eight who is watching you for signs of danger. A friend. A person who has decided that you are worth the particular investment of trust that friendship requires—the investment that has no return, no close, no score, just the daily compounding of showing up and being present and walking along a river in March while the light tries to be spring.

'Thank you,' you say.

'For what?'

'For letting me through.'

She laughs. The laugh is easy and full and it carries across the water and for a moment the East River has Margaux's laugh in it, and the river holds the laugh the way the gold ceiling held the light, gently, without comment, without keeping track.

'Don't make it weird,' she says. And you don't."

Section 7 - Marcus

The player has a number called marcus-state. The marcus-state of the player is 0.

Talking-to-Marcus is an action applying to nothing. Understand "talk to marcus" or "call marcus" or "text marcus" as talking-to-Marcus when the relationship is happening.

Check talking-to-Marcus:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "Marcus is a text on your phone. The text says: sorry bro, work thing, next time." instead.

Carry out talking-to-Marcus:
	increase the marcus-state of the player by 1;
	if the marcus-state of the player is 1:
		say "You text Marcus. Not the way you used to text Marcus—not logistics, not which venue, not target-rich or dead or let's bounce. You text him the way a person texts a friend: [italic type]Hey. Want to get a beer?[roman type]

He responds in four minutes. [italic type]Yeah. When?[roman type]

Friday. A bar on Avenue B that is not a venue and has never been scouted for set density and has a jukebox that plays Springsteen if you hit it in the right place. You are sitting in a booth when he arrives, and the arriving is strange because the last time you were supposed to see Marcus you were standing on East Seventy-Sixth Street in a blazer and he was a text on your phone that said [italic type]sorry bro, work thing[roman type] and the text was the hinge the whole evening turned on—if he had come, you would have been a two-man team running the method, and the method with a wing is a different method, smoother, more calibrated, and maybe Catherine would have been closed faster or maybe she would have seen the machinery more clearly, two men performing instead of one, and maybe she would have left, and maybe the leaving would have been the right thing, and none of this happened because Marcus had a work thing.

He is shorter than you remember. Or you are taller. Or the proportions have shifted because you are no longer looking at him through the method's lens, where Marcus was the wing, where Marcus had a function, where Marcus existed in relation to the set the way the hammer exists in relation to the nail. He is just a guy. Brown jacket, needs a haircut, tired around the eyes in a way that is new. He is just your friend.

'So,' he says, sitting down. 'You're seeing someone.'

'How do you know?'

'Because you texted me like a person instead of like a tactician. The old you would have said [italic type]let's hit the Carlyle Thursday, I've been running sets and I need a wing.[roman type] The new you said [italic type]want to get a beer.[roman type]' He picks up the menu. 'A beer is not a mission. A beer is a beer. Something happened.'

'Something happened,' you say.";
	otherwise if the marcus-state of the player is 2:
		say "You tell Marcus about Catherine. Not all of it—not the kino ladder, not the compliance test, not the scores. You tell him about the evening the way a person tells a friend about meeting someone: the bar, the gold ceiling, the conversation, the walk outside, the cab, the morning after. You tell him about the eggplant and the cat and the fire escapes and the shoes by the door. You tell him about Margaux. You tell him that Catherine knew.

Marcus listens. He drinks his beer. He is not running analysis. He is not thinking about what he would have done differently, how he would have calibrated, where your game was tight and where it was loose. He is listening the way people listen when the thing being said is about a life and not about a technique.

'I'm glad,' he says, when you are finished. And the gladness is simple and unperformative and it sits between you on the table like the two beers—just there, taking up space, not trying to be anything.

'Are you still—' you start, and you do not finish, because the finishing would require saying the words, and the words feel different now, the way a tool you have put down feels different from a tool you are holding.

'On the forum?' He shrugs. 'I read it sometimes. The way you read anything you used to be into. Like checking on a place you used to live.' He turns the beer glass. 'I went on a date last month. A woman from my office. We got dinner. I did not neg her. I did not DHV. I told her I liked her shoes and I meant it. The shoes were good.' He smiles. 'It didn't go anywhere. But it was—I was there. I was in the room. The whole time, I was in the room. That felt new.'

'It is new.'

'Yeah.' He drinks. 'Hey, do you remember the time we went to that rooftop thing in Bushwick and you opened a three-set and the obstacle literally walked away mid-sentence?'

'I remember.'

'That was the worst night of my life,' he says, and he is laughing, and you are laughing, and the laughing is the kind of laughing that only happens between two people who shared something and survived it and can look back at the surviving from a distance where the distance is the comedy, because comedy is tragedy plus time, and the time is five months, and five months is enough.

'We were idiots,' you say.

'We were idiots,' he agrees. 'But we were trying. That's what I keep thinking about. We were trying so hard. The trying was real even when everything else was—' he waves his hand, the gesture Margaux made, the gesture Catherine made, the universal gesture for the shape of a thing you can see but not name.

'Performed,' you say.

'Performed,' he says. 'The trying was real and the performance was real and they were both happening at the same time and neither one cancelled the other out. I think about that a lot.'

The jukebox plays Springsteen. The bar is warm. Marcus orders another round. You are two men in a booth on Avenue B drinking beer and talking about the time they were idiots, and the talking is not a debrief and not a field report and not a strategy session. The talking is just talking. The beer is just beer. The friend is just a friend.

'Bring her next time,' Marcus says. 'Catherine. I want to meet the woman who broke your algorithm.'

'She didn't break it,' you say. 'She just—waited. Until I stopped running it.'

'Same thing,' Marcus says. And maybe it is.";
	otherwise:
		say "You and Marcus are friends. Not method friends, not wingmen, not two nodes in a tactical network. Friends. You get beers on Fridays when you can. He tells you about work. You tell him about Catherine. He tells you about the woman from his office—they went on a second date, then a third, and the third one he cooked for her and burned the rice and she helped him clean the pot and the helping-clean-the-pot was, he says, the most intimate thing that has happened to him in years. You understand this. You understand this completely. The pot, the burned rice, the helping—these are the things that happen when the method ends and the life begins, and the life is made of pots and rice and the specific gravity of a person who stays to help you clean."

Section 8 - The Therapist

The player has a number called therapy-state. The therapy-state of the player is 0.

Going-to-therapy is an action applying to nothing. Understand "therapy" or "go to therapy" or "see therapist" or "therapist" as going-to-therapy when the relationship is happening.

Check going-to-therapy:
	if the relationship is not happening:
		say "You have a therapist. You have had a therapist for two years. You have never told your therapist anything that mattered." instead.

Carry out going-to-therapy:
	increase the therapy-state of the player by 1;
	if the therapy-state of the player is 1:
		say "You have had a therapist for two years. Her name is Dr. Rosen and her office is on West Eighty-Third Street and the office has a white noise machine outside the door and two chairs and a box of tissues and a clock you can see from your chair that she cannot see from hers, which you suspect is deliberate.

For two years you have gone every other Wednesday and talked about work and sleep and your parents' divorce and the vague ambient dissatisfaction that sits at the center of your life like a piece of furniture you keep walking around but never move. You have never mentioned the forum. You have never mentioned the method. You have never mentioned the book on the shelf between the Murakami and the Gladwell. These omissions were not lies exactly—they were architecture. You built the therapy around the method the way the method built the evening around the set, leaving the most important thing in the room unexamined, tucked behind the furniture, visible only if you knew where to look.

Today is Wednesday. You sit in the chair. The white noise machine hums. Dr. Rosen waits. She is a good waiter. Waiting is, you suspect, ninety percent of her profession—waiting for the person in the chair to arrive at the thing they came to say, the way the doorman at the Carlyle waits for people to arrive at the door, the way the pianist waits for the room to be ready for the next song.

'Something's different,' she says.

'I met someone,' you say. And then, before you can organize it or sequence it or build a framework around it: 'I met someone at a bar in November and I was running a system on her—a system I learned from a book, a system for approaching women, a system with steps and techniques and a vocabulary, and the system worked, and she came home with me, and we've been seeing each other for three months, and she knew the whole time what I was doing, and she came home with me anyway, and I don't know why, and I don't know why I'm telling you this now except that for two years I've been sitting in this chair talking about my sleep and my parents and I never told you about the system and the system was the thing, it was the whole thing, it was the architecture of my evenings and my weekends and my self-concept and I never mentioned it and I think the reason I never mentioned it is that mentioning it would have made it visible and making it visible would have been the beginning of putting it down and I was not ready to put it down.

'I think I'm ready to put it down.'

She does not say anything. She waits. The waiting is not strategic. The waiting is the clearing—the opening in which things become visible, the space that exists before and beneath all the techniques and frameworks and systems, the space that is just two people in a room and one of them is talking and one of them is listening and the listening is not a method and the talking is not a performance and the room is not a venue and the white noise machine is making the small sound of a world that is giving you permission to be heard.

You talk for forty-five minutes. You do not arrive at conclusions. You do not achieve insights. You do not solve the problem, because the problem is not a problem—the problem is a life, and lives are not solved, they are lived, and the living is what you have been doing, unevenly, imperfectly, with the specific awkwardness of a person who learned the mechanics before the meaning and is now, three months into a relationship with a woman who has a cat named Bartleby, beginning to understand that the meaning was always there, underneath the mechanics, the way the ground is always there underneath the floor, and the floor is what you built to not have to feel the ground, and the ground is what holds you up, and the holding-up was happening the whole time, and you did not need the floor, and the floor was the method, and the method was the floor.

Dr. Rosen says: 'Same time in two weeks?'

'Yeah,' you say. 'Same time in two weeks.'

You walk out onto West Eighty-Third Street. The air is March air—cold but with something in it, something that is not yet warmth but is the promise of warmth, the way the clearing is not yet seeing but is the promise of seeing. You stand on the sidewalk. You do not have a three-second rule. You do not have a next move. You have a Wednesday and a therapist and a girlfriend and a cat that sits on your lap and a friend who burned rice for a woman and a friend who makes documentaries about vanishing languages and a doorman who has been opening the same door for thirty-one years and a bartender who remembers what everyone drinks and a pianist who plays for the weather and a diner man who has had the same pen for eleven years and a gold ceiling you looked up at once in November and can still see when you close your eyes.

You walk home. The city walks with you. The clearing is open.";
	otherwise:
		say "You go to therapy. You talk. Not about the method—about Catherine, about Bartleby, about the eggplant and the shoes by the door and the sound engineer in Kutaisi and the burned rice and the bar on Avenue B and the manuscript about the Black Sea. You talk about your life. Your actual life. The one that is happening while you are in it. Dr. Rosen listens. The listening is the room. The room is enough."

Section 9 - The Endings

Instead of leaving the Carlyle when the relationship is happening:
	say "You think about leaving. Not Catherine—just the thought of leaving, the way you sometimes think about rain while standing in the sun, a hypothetical that has no weight, a door you could walk through but won't because the room you are in is warm and the person in it is warm and the cat in it is warm and the warmth is not strategic and not performed and not optimized. The warmth is just warm.

You are lying in a bed with a woman and a cat and the radiator is clicking and the city is humming and the book is on the shelf and the book is just a book—not a secret, not a weapon, not a confession waiting to be made. A book you read once. A thing that happened. The way meeting someone at a bar is a thing that happened, the way the gold ceiling is a thing that happened, the way the rabbits in their top hats are a thing that happened. Things happen. Some of them bring you to other things. You are here now. You are in the here.

Outside, the city is doing what the city does. The traffic lights are cycling. The diner man is finishing his crossword. The doorman at the Carlyle is opening the door for someone else. James is pouring something precise. The pianist is playing for the room. Everything is continuing. Everything was always continuing. You are part of the continuing now. You are a Thursday and a Saturday and sometimes a snowstorm Wednesday. You are a second mug taken from the back of the cabinet. You are a life becoming a life for two, and the becoming is not dramatic, it is not cinematic, it is quiet, it is Tuesday, it is coffee in the morning and pasta on Thursdays and a cat who prefers not to but sits on your lap anyway, and the sitting-on-your-lap-anyway is a form of grace you did not earn and do not need to earn because grace is not earned. Grace is the cat deciding.

'Okay,' you say. To no one. To the radiator. To Bartleby. To the city. To Catherine, who is asleep. To yourself.

'Okay.'";
	end the story saying "The clearing is open."

When the relationship ends:
	end the story saying "The clearing is open."

Part Seven - The Author's Note

The author-note is a text that varies. The author-note is "This game was written in the winter of 2026 by a human and a machine, in the way that a song is written by a person and a piano—the person brings the idea, the instrument brings the range. The human brought Bemelmans Bar and the method and the rabbit at the edge of the frozen pond. The machine brought the gold ceiling and the ice that thinks about becoming water and the field report that does not have a field for the things that matter. Neither of them is sure who brought the listening. It may have been both. It may have been neither. It may have been the room.

The game has a main quest and it has the rest of the evening. The main quest is the method: approach, neg, DHV, befriend, isolate, kino, close. The main quest works. You can follow it from the door to the number and the game will cooperate at every step. But the game was also built around the main quest the way Bemelmans Bar was built around the bar—the walls are wider than the counter, and the murals are on the walls, and the rabbits are in the murals, and the rabbits are the real thing, and the real thing was always on the walls, and the walls were always wider than the counter, and you were always free to look up.

Inside the vast Romanesque church the tourists jostled in the half darkness. Vault after vault and no overview. A few candle-flames flickered. An angel with no face embraced me and whispered through my whole body: Don't be ashamed of being human, be proud! Inside you, vault opens behind vault endlessly. You will never be complete, and that is as it should be."
